# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] The **Aisne** (/eɪn/ *ayn*, US also /ɛn/ *en*, French: [ɛːn] ⓘ; Picard: *Ainne*) is a river in northeastern France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] It gave its name to the French department of Aisne.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] It was known in the Roman period as **Axona**.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] The river rises in the forest of Argonne, at Rembercourt-Sommaisne, near Sainte-Menehould.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] It flows north and then west before joining the Oise near Compiègne.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] The Aisne is 356 kilometres (221 mi) long.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] Its main tributaries are the Vesle, the Aire and the Suippe.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] The Battle of the Axona was fought between the Romans and the Belgae near the Aisne in 57 BC.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] Three Battles of the Aisne were fought in the Aisne valley during the First World War.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] The river Aisne was used for commercial navigation as early as the Celtic period, and rafts were floated from a long distance above the present limit of navigation at Vailly-sur-Aisne until the mid-19th century.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] Canalisation works were begun in 1836, at the same time as construction of the Canal lateral à l'Aisne.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] The canal was completed first, in 1841, then two years later the river navigation.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] Commercial traffic in *péniches* carrying 220 tonnes is still active, while recreational traffic is mainly private boats.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] The waterway is 57 kilometres (35 mi) long, from the river Oise to the junction with the lateral canal, and has 7 locks.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] Through the lateral canal, it links with the Marne and the Canal de la Meuse.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/aisne-river] The kilometre distances continue the numbering from Canal latéral à l'Aisne from east to west.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Pierluigi Farnese and Girolama Orsini were married in Rome on 6 August 1519.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Young Alessandro studied at Bologna along with his cousin, Guido Ascanio Sforza di Santa Fiora.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was a member of the Collegio Ancarano, which had been founded in the 15th century by Petrus de Ancarano in Tuscia, for students specializing in legal studies.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 18 December 1534, at the age of 14, he was appointed Cardinal Deacon of Sant'Angelo in Pescheria by his grandfather Paul III, who had been elected to the papacy two months previously.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 11 August 1535, he was appointed Abbot Commendatory of the Abbey of Tre Fontane on the Via Ostiense, a position he held until 1544.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In 1535, he was also appointed Abbot commendatory of S. Étienne de Caën.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Young Cardinal Farnese received many other offices and benefices, becoming Vice-Chancellor of the Holy Roman Church (13 August 1535 – 2 March 1589), He also became Governor of Tivoli (1535–1550), Archpriest of St.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Mary Major Basilica (1537–1543), Archpriest of St.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 27 August 1539, at the age of 18, Alessandro Farnese was named titular Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem; he vacated the office on the appointment of a new Patriarch on 28 February 1550.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The office was highly lucrative, the duties were nominal and did not necessarily involve episcopal functions.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In 1538, he was appointed Pope Paul III's principal Secretary and, with the assistance of Monsignor (Msgr.) Marcello Cervino, he managed most of the papal business until 1549.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In 1541, Cardinal Farnese was named Protector of the Holy Roman Empire before the Holy See and Protector of Spain before the Holy See.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] These offices made him the most prominent expediter of all Imperial and Spanish business in the Roman Curia; his opinion was always consulted and, since he was the Pope's nephew, it was often followed.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] At the same time, he was appointed Papal Legate in Avignon (1541–1565).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] From 1564 to 1565, he was Bishop of Sabina and it is conjectured (in the absence of positive evidence) that it was in 1564 that Farnese finally was consecrated a bishop.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was certainly a bishop when he was the principal Consecrator of Cardinal Giulio della Rovere on 15 April 1566.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] From 1565 to 1578, he was Bishop of Tusculum (Frascati).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was the Bishop of Porto from 9 July 1578 to 5 December 1580.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was then Cardinal-Bishop of Ostia and Velletri and Dean of the College of Cardinals from 5 December 1580 until his death on 2 March 1589.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] His grandfather, Pope Paul III, immediately named Alessandro Farnese Administrator of the Diocese of Parma (1 November 1534), allowing him to collect the episcopal income during the interregnum.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Alessandro resigned on 13 August 1535, when Cardinal Guido Ascanio Sforza di Santa Fiora, another grandson of Paul III and only two years older than Alessandro, was named the new Administrator (enjoying his Parmesan income until he resigned in 1560).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Farnese was appointed Administrator of Jaen, Spain, from 30 July 1535 until another Administrator, Cardinal Alessandro Cesarini, was appointed on 6 July 1537.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was Administrator of the Archdiocese of Avignon from 1535 to 1551 and of the Diocese of Vizeu, Portugal (1547–1552).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 9 May 1536, the Emperor Charles V named Cardinal Farnese as the new archbishop of Monreale in Sicily; his appointment was confirmed on 15 May 1536, by Pope Paul III.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] But Monreale was not a happy place, since the monks of the Cathedral of Monreale and the clergy of the diocese were in one squabble after another with each other.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 26 July 1549, the Pope was forced to intervene, in a letter in which he referred to the Cardinal under the title of *perpetuus Administrator*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] A Vicar was appointed for the underage and absentee Archbishop, Msgr.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Giovanni Antonio Fassari, titular Bishop of Christopolis in Greece; he was succeeded in 1546 by Pompeo Zambecari.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Giovanni Pietro Fortiguerra, Bishop of Cyrene in Libya., The Cardinal allowed the Jesuits to found a college in Monreale, and allowed the priests of the Society to work in the diocese.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In 1568, Cardinal Farnese visited his diocese and held a synod.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was accompanied by his librarian, the famous antiquarian and papal biographer, Onofrio Panvinio, who, unhappily, died at Palermo on 16 (?) March 1568.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Cardinal continued to enjoy the income of the diocese until 1573, when he resigned the bishopric.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 17 June 1537, Farnese was appointed Administrator of the Diocese of Bitonto in the Kingdom of Naples on the resignation of Bishop Lopez de Alarcon; his administration ceased upon the appointment of a new bishop on 8 January 1538.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 16 July 1540, Farnese was named Administrator of the Diocese of Cavaillon in Provence, which he resigned one year later on 20 July 1541.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In 1549, his grandfather Pope Paul III died.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was Administrator of the Archdiocese of Tours from 28 April 1553, until Pope Julius III ordered the issue of bulls for Archbishop Simon de Mailly on 25 June 1554.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In the case of Tours, the right of nomination belonged to the King of France, Henri II, whose daughter Diane had married Farnese's youngest brother Orazio in 1552.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 25 June 1554, the same day that his administration of Tours ceased, Farnese was appointed Administrator of the Diocese of Viviers, which lasted until the Pope approved King Henri's nomination of a new bishop on 12 November 1554.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was likewise nominated by the King of France to be Administrator of the Diocese of Cahors, the appointment being approved by Pope Julius III on 12 November 1554; a new bishop was approved by Pope Paul IV on 7 May 1557, ending his appointment.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] There had been two Conclaves in the interim, accounting probably for the length of his Administration of Cahors.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In 1555, Cardinal Farnese was named Administrator of the Diocese of Spoleto, a post he held until a new bishop was appointed on 16 December 1562.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Alessandro Farnese also served as Administrator of the Archdiocese of Benevento from 22 November 1556, until a new archbishop was approved by Paul IV on 14 January 1558.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] All of these appointments should be considered as opportunities for financial enrichment, not opportunities for service in vineyards of the Lord far from Rome.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The various administrations were carried out by authorized agents.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In 1564, Alessandro Farnese succeeded his brother Ranuccio as Abbot Commendatory of the Monastery of Farfa, which he held until his death in 1589.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] It was he who introduced the Benedictine monks of the Congregation of Monte Cassino into the monastery in 1567.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He also built, or rebuilt, the monastery's water supply.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Farnese also became a Papal Legate, arranging peace between the perpetually warring Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor and Francis I of France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In the Consistory of 24 November 1539 he was sent as Apostolic *Legatus a latere* to attempt to arrange a peace between the two feuding monarchs.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He left Rome on 29 November and entered Paris on 31 December.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was in Rouen on 14 January 1540, met with the King on 14 February.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He then left for Flanders on 17 February for a meeting with the Emperor; he stayed for three months, and returned to Paris on 14 May.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He had a meeting with King Francis on the 17th at Saint-Germain-en-Laye.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Farnese was named *Legatus a latere* again, and for the same purpose, at the Consistory of 21 November 1543.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He arrived at Fontainebleau on 29 December 1543 and remained until 6 January 1544, when he departed for Bruxelles to visit the Emperor.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He arrived on 14 January, and was back in France by 4 February.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In 1546, he accompanied the troops sent by the pope to the aid of Charles V against the Schmalkaldic League.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In 1548, Cardinal Alessandro Farnese took into his service as his private secretary Annibale Caro, the noted poet and prose stylist.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Caro had previously been in the service of Cardinal Alessandro's father, Pierluigi Farnese, and after his murder on 10 September 1547, to Duke Ottavio Farnese, and then to Cardinal Ranuccio Farnese, his own younger brother.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In 1551, Cardinal Alessandro was sent by Pope Julius III to convince his brother Ottavio, the Duke of Parma and Piacenza, to surrender those territories, which, the Pope said were fiefs of the Church.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Farnese had spent more than fifteen years developing their dukedom, and Cardinal Alessandro's father had been assassinated in the struggle with the Gonzaga and the Emperor Charles over it.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Farnese were being protected by the French Crown, which considered Parma its entrée into northern Italy, where it challenged the Emperor to the possession of the Duchy of Milan and the Lombard plain.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Julius was toying with explosive material.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Ottavio refused, and Alessandro supported him.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Farnese had a complete breach in relations with the Pope, and Alessandro was immediately unwelcome in Rome.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Pope Julius sequestrated his diocese of Monreale, and confiscated all of the moveables in the Palazzo Farnese, said to have been worth 30,000 scudi.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He withdrew in April, first to a visit with his sister Vittoria, the Duchess of Urbino, then to Florence, and finally to Avignon.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] After peace was made between the Pope and France, Orazio Farnese had the Duchy of Castro restored to him (1552) and, to protect the Farnese's French connection, Orazio married Diane de France, the illegitimate daughter of Henri II.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Unfortunately, Cardinal Farnese's brother Orazio was killed in battle on 18 July 1553, leaving no heirs.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The dukedoms went to their younger brother Ottavio Farnese.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Farnese had been in France, when on 6 June 1554 he was appointed by Henri II to go to Rome and take charge of French affairs in the absence of Cardinal d'Este, who was in Parma—over the objections of Cardinal du Bellay, who did not appreciate being supplanted.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal d'Este was ruling Parma on behalf of the French king, who had acquired the duchy from Paul III as the price of an alliance.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In November, Henri named a new Ambassador to the Holy See, and Cardinal Farnese was free to return to France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Farnese did not participate in the first conclave of 1555, 5 – 9 April, which followed the death of Julius III.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He had been in Avignon, serving as Legate and avoiding the unwelcome attention of the Pope.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] But, on the news of the death of Pope Julius, he took the road for Rome.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was carrying letters from Henri II of France to the College of Cardinals and to individual cardinals, in favor of Cardinal Reginald Pole.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He did not arrive, however, until after the middle of the month of April.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Louis de Guise-Lorraine, also travelling from France, arrived on the 21st.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In fact, only two French cardinals were in Rome, thereby giving the Imperial faction a great advantage.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The bull was completely ignored by the Cardinals already in Rome, and only the *Novendiales* were observed.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In accordance with older instructions direct from Henri II, the French faction was supporting Cardinal d'Este, then the Cardinal de Tournon (who was not present at the Conclave), and then Cardinal du Bellay.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Emperor, as in the Conclave of 1550, had a preference for Cardinal Reginald Pole, the Papal Legate in England.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] D'Este was not electable (Sir John Masone, the English agent wrote: "Marry, we hear of no quality to set him forward but that he is rich."), though the six votes he received in the first ballot caused considerable consternation, and the beginning of a "Stop D'Este" movement.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Some of the cleverer cardinals, led by Carafa and Madruzzi of Trent, realized that, when all the opinions were factored in, there were very few electable cardinals, the best of whom was Cardinal Marcello Cervini.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was a reformer, he was strict, and he was uncorrupted; he was opposed to nepotism.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Unfortunately, Cervini was disliked by the Emperor.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] But the genuine reformers, who wanted the resumption of the Council of Trent, worked with Carafa and Madruzzi to produce a two-thirds majority.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Among them were Ranuccio Farnese, Farnese's brother, and Guido Ascanio Sforza, his first-cousin.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] When Farnese finally arrived from Avignon in mid-April, he was no doubt delighted to find his grandfather's secretary, Cardinal Marcello Cervini, on the throne of Peter.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Unfortunately, on the morning of the 18th, Pope Marcellus II showed symptoms of a fever and in the night between 30 April and 1 May, he died.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] But even before Marcellus was dead, Cardinal Farnese wrote directly to Henri II, urging him to send the French cardinals to Rome immediately.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The second Conclave of 1555 opened on 15 May, with the same cardinals as in April, but with the addition of eight late arrivals.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The leading candidate seemed to be Cardinal Carafa, the Inquisitor, but he was told to his face by the Imperial Ambassador that the Emperor Charles V did not want him as Pope.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Imperial faction was favoring Cardinals Carpi, Morone, and Pole.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Pole also seemed to have French support, but there was an influential group, led by Carafa, Carpi, and Alvarez (all professional Inquisitors), who openly questioned the orthodoxy of Pole and of Morone.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] D'Avanson also had to break the news that Cardinal du Bellay, out of personal ambition, had broken ranks and would support Cardinal Carafa.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In the voting, the Imperial candidate, Cardinal Carpi, seemed to be moving forward, until the French faction and the cardinals created by Julius III (of which there were fifteen at the Conclave) combined to put him out of the running.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Once it was clear that nobody in the French faction was going to succeed, Cardinal Farnese and Cardinal d'Este decided to throw their support to Cardinal Carafa.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Imperial faction was so frightened at what Pope Carafa might do in trying to get Naples out of the hands of the Emperor that they sent Cardinals Corner and Ricci to Alessandro Farnese to beg him to abandon Carafa and accept their votes *for himself*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] But Farnese was not so foolish as to believe that he could be successful without the endorsement either of the Emperor or of the King of France—and he had neither.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The supporters of Carafa finally numbered more than the two-thirds needed for election, but the Imperialists (who were caucusing in the Hall of the Secret Consistory) refused to come to the chapel and carry out the electoral process.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] It was Farnese who, using both blandishments and threats, managed to get the Imperialists to give in and assemble with the rest of the cardinals in the Cappella Paolina.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On the afternoon of 23 May, the Feast of the Ascension, the seventy-eight year old Cardinal Gian Pietro Carafa of Naples was elected pope by acclamation.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He had been the co-founder of the Theatine Order, and was a promoter of reform in the Church.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was no humanist, however, and preferred the doctrine of Thomas Aquinas.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was also a vigorous opponent of Protestantism, and anything that favored it.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He saw heretics everywhere, even inside the College of Cardinals, and as an Inquisitor he showed no scruple or mercy for those who were tainted.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Showing all of the traditional prejudices against the Jews, and especially against converted Jews, he issued a bull on 14 July 1555, *Cum nimis absurdum*, creating the Jewish Ghetto of Rome.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He refused to recognize the election of Ferdinand I as Holy Roman Emperor, and he refused to recognize the retirement of Charles V.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He ruled until his death on 18 August 1559, or rather his nephew, Cardinal Carlo Carafa, did.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] It was only three months before his death that Paul IV was fully informed of the misdeeds of his nephews, Cardinal Carafa, Giovanni Caraffa Duke of Paliano, and Antonio Carafa Marchese of Montebello.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] When the Florentine Ambassador, Bongiano Gianfiliazzi, had attempted to have an audience with Paul IV to enlighten him about his corrupt nephews, the door was slammed in his face by Cardinal Carafa.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Obviously, there was no room in the Curia for the advice of Cardinal Farnese.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] There was considerable danger to Farnese properties because of Paul IV's anti-imperial policy.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] It was in 1556 that Cardinal Farnese commissioned Giacomo Barozzi da Vignola to take in hand the half-completed fortress at Caprarola and turn it into a country villa.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Actual construction began in 1559 and was completed in 1573.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Even when half completed, in 1561, Cardinal Alessandro commissioned Taddeo Zuccari and his workshop to decorate the rooms on the lower floor.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Stanza della solitudine was decorated by the same artists between 1563 and 1565, in accordance with a design created by Onufrio Panvinio.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Farnese retired to Parma in the meantime (1557), where he stayed with his brother, Duke Ottavio.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] It was there and at that time that they were approached with peace feelers by Cardinal Carafa, who was even willing to marry one of the Carafas to young Duke Alessandro, the son of Ottavio and Margaret of Parma.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Nonetheless, Cardinal Alessandro's influence in Rome was considerable.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was named Cardinal Protector of the Empire (14 September 1541), Sicily, of Aragon (13 December 1565), of Portugal, of Poland, of the Republic of Genoa, and of Ragusa.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Carafa was elected, and began dealing with real or imagined enemies.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] First Ascanio della Corgna came under suspicion.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was general of the papal cavalry, and was actually suspected of being loyal to the Emperor.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Angelo, along with his brother, Cardinal della Corgna (27 July 1556).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The cardinal had been Administrator of the Diocese of Spoleto on the appointment of Julius III, but Paul IV immediately replaced him with Cardinal Alessandro Farnese.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The charge against the cardinal that brought him to the Castel S.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Angelo was that he had attempted to open communications with Philip II of Spain.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The pressure of Spanish victories in Lombardy and Tuscany, however, forced their release.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Then it was the turn of Cardinal Morone, a man of tested prudence and familiar with Germany.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He had been chosen as the Papal Legate to the Imperial Diet in Augsburg, on the insistence of both Charles V and his brother Ferdinand.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He received the Legatine cross on 13 February 1555, and was in Augsburg on 23 March, the day Pope Julius III died.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He therefore arrived in Rome too late for the April Conclave.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In the second Conclave, a month later, both Pole and Morone were Imperial candidates, but Cardinal Carafa (a candidate himself) loudly voiced his suspicions that both were heretics.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Suddenly, on 31 May 1557, Morone was arrested by the Pope's nephew and Secretary of State personally.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Pietro Carnesecchi, a former adherent of Morone, wrote: "Why Morone is imprisoned, no one knows; many say that the Cardinals have brought it about, in order that he may be out of their way at the next election of a Pope, when he would get the greatest number of votes.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Pope intends summoning all the Cardinals to Rome, that they as a college may judge Morone." There was an immediate outcry.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The cardinals wanted a Congregation be held at which explanations would be demanded.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Paul IV took the initiative and held a Congregation at which he presided, telling the cardinals that it was not politics but the honor of God that was involved.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The process against Morone would be carried out by the members of the Inquisition.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Twenty-one charges were levelled at him.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 12 June 1557, Morone was interrogated in the Castel S.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Angelo by the committee: Cardinals Innocenzo del Monte, Jean Suau, Scipione Rebiba, Spoletano [Alessandro Farnese], and Michele Ghislieri.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Having examined him and heard his extensive rejoinders, the committee reported in favor of Morone but Paul IV was not satisfied.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Angelo until the death of Paul IV, when the College of Cardinals ordered his release.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Rebiba was sent as Nuncio to France, to discuss the matter of an alliance with Henri II.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] For two decades, the Farnese had been trying to maintain friendships both with King Henri II of France and the Emperor Charles V of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] This became more difficult when Cardinal Carafa, in the name of Paul IV, concluded a treaty with Henri II on 23 July 1556, committing them to a war against the Emperor for the Kingdom of Naples.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 23 October 1557, Henri struck against Cardinal Alessandro Farnese, issuing letters patent by which he confiscated all of the benefices of the Cardinal which he still enjoyed in France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Abbeys of St. Étienne de Caën, Beauport in Brittany, and Granselve, as well as the Administratorship of the Diocese of Viviers, were also included.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In the document, Henri complained of the Cardinal and his brothers taking the part of the King of Spain.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The total loss for the Cardinal alone amounted to more than 30.000 francs.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The benefices were all given to Cardinal Ippolito II d'Este, Farnese's enemy, who had spent his youth at the French Court and was a personal friend of Henri and the Royal Family.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] These losses were in addition to those inflicted by Pope Julius III, whose election had been opposed by Cardinal Farnese in the interest of Pope Paul III's secretary, Marcello Cervini.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] One of those was the Governorship of Tivoli, which also went to Cardinal d'Este.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Another was the Patriarchate of Jerusalem, which was granted away only twenty days after the end of the Conclave.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] But Julius III (Monte) had died in 1555, as had Marcellus II (Cervini).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Emperor Charles V had retired in 1556 and died in 1558 and both Paul IV and Henri II died in 1559, within a month of each other.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] For the approaching Conclave, King Philip II of Spain let it be known that his choices were Cardinals Rodolfo Pio de Carpi, Giacomo Puteo, Giovanni Angelo de' Medici, and Clemente d' Olera.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In contrast, the French king François II was promoting the nomination of Cardinals Ippolito d'Este, François de Tournon, and Ercole Gonzaga.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Farnese, who was 38 years old and the senior Cardinal Deacon by this point, disliked both d'Este and his cousin Gonzaga, and therefore decided to do everything he could to see the election of Carpi.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Farnese could only effectively directly influence four or five of the votes, and so had to work in alliance with another group - allying himself with the cardinals created by Paul IV and who were being led by his nephew, Cardinal Carlo Carafa.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] This eventually led to the election of Cardinal de' Medici, and Farnese crowned the new pope on 6 January 1560.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The new Cardinal Nephews were Carlo Borromeo and Markus Sittich von Hohenems Altemps.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] During the reign of Pope Pius IV, Cardinal Farnese enjoyed good fortune.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Pope was a friend of his, and he was able to avoid the unpleasantries of international affairs, as he built a circle of friends in the College of Cardinals and in the Roman Curia.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 14 April 1564, Cardinal Farnese was promoted to the title of Cardinal Priest of S.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Lorenzo in Damaso, a post he held for less than a month.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 12 May, he was promoted to the Order of Cardinal Bishops with the diocese of Sabina.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He distanced himself from the horrors surrounding the fall of the Carafa nephews in 1561.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Pius was not a healthy man, and his anticipated demise gave Farnese and others time to plan.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Pope Pius IV (Medici) died on 9 December 1565.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The French, at this time Catherine de' Medici, having learned nothing from 1555 or 1559, still offered their support to Cardinal Ippolito d'Este.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] King Philip II favored d' Olera, Ghislieri, Ricci, Morone, and Pacecho.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] When the Spanish Ambassador, Don Luis Requesens de Zuniga, arrived in Rome on 21 December 1565, however, he carried instructions to support Ghislieri and Morone.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was suspicious of the orthodoxy of Cardinal Morone though, and he feared that Cardinal Farnese might pursue a vendetta against Spain for the murder of his father if he were to become pope.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Emperor Maximilian II was informed by his agent in Rome, Nosti Camiani, that the most favored cardinals were: d' Olera, Boncompagni, Suau, Sirleto, Simonetta, Gianbernardino Scotti, and Michele Ghislieri.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He wrote directly to Cosimo III of Florence, asking for his assistance in the election.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cosimo replied that he was no longer in the business of influencing papal elections, but agreed to serve the Emperor's wishes.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was in fact very active behind the scenes.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He wanted a pope who would make him Duke of Tuscany, and would validate his control over Siena, and he had already picked out Cardinal Ghislieri.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Duchess of Ferrara, a daughter of the Emperor, was recommending Cardinal Francesco Gonzaga, the 27 year old nephew of Cardinal Ercole Gonzaga (who had died in 1563), for whom she was soliciting the Emperor, the Duke of Savoy and the King of France, Francois II.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Duchess of Savoy was pushing for Cardinal Ferrero, who was only 28 years old.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The nephews of Pius IV, Cardinal Borromeo and Cardinal Altemps, had another candidate in mind, the Nuncio in Spain, Cardinal Ugo Boncompagni, and they sent a swift galley to fetch him.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] And then there was Cardinal Alessandro Farnese, who was campaigning for himself.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] There were fifty-two cardinals in attendance on 20 December 1565.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Seventeen cardinals were under the age of forty, seven of whom were under the age of thirty.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Farnese, nephew of Pope Paul III, had in his faction Cardinals Corregio, Gambara, Savelli, Paleotti and Orsini.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Farnese was personally beloved by the Roman populace as a patron of the poor and a Maecenas of the arts.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The cardinals who had been created by Paul IV were also supporting Farnese.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] They included: Vitelli (the Camerlengo), Capizucchi, Reuman Suau, Rebiba, Ghislieri, and D' Olera.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The cardinals created by Pius IV numbered nine, and under certain circumstances might draw four more.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The cardinals created by Julius III numbered five.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Florentines had between four and six.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Six French cardinals did not come to the Conclave at all.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The large number of factions would present a major difficulty for anyone trying to put together a two-thirds majority.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Nationality was not the only way of dividing up the cardinals either.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] There were the seniors and the juniors, and the eager reformers and the complacent majority.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] As soon as the Conclave opened, Cardinal Borromeo, who, as the nephew of the late pope, considered himself a leader, if not a pope-maker, approached Cardinal Farnese, who had the largest number of commitments.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He indicated that he thought that Cardinal Morone should be pope.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] This was in accordance with the wishes of the Emperor, and Morone had been one of the Presidents of the Council of Trent.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Farnese seemed friendly and willing to please, which Borromeo (wrongly) took as an agreement to supply votes.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In addition, there were those who did not like Morone personally.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] It is alleged that both Alessandro Farnese and Ippolito d'Este had grudges against Morone due to decisions which he had made while Legate in Bologna.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] His enemies could always muster more than one-third of the college to block his election.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] When it came to a vote, Morone got twenty-nine votes.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Farnese must have realized that he was in somewhat the same situation himself.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He could muster between twenty-eight and thirty votes, but not the thirty-five needed to elect.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In his straightforward way, Borromeo then went on to his second candidate, Cardinal Sirleto, but he too failed.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Borromeo went to Farnese, and stated flatly that he was not going to support Farnese in the current Conclave, and he asked Farnese to help him in choosing a worthy pope.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Farnese suggested the names of four cardinals whom he would support: Gianbernardino Scotti (Trani), D' Olera (Aracoeli), Ghislieri (Alessandrino) and Ricci (Montepulciano).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Within two hours, they had sufficient votes to elect Ghislieri.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] That afternoon, the Cardinals assembled and took a vote; two cardinals voted from their sickbeds.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The votes were not by secret ballot, but out loud.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Ghislieri was elected unanimously and took the name Pius V.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] By 1569, the Cardinal was *Legatus perpetuus* (Permanent legate) of the province of the Patrimony of St.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] This is recorded on the inscription of a new town gate.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In 1569, Cardinal Alessandro Farnese made his journey to Sicily, to inspect his Archdiocese of Monreale.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Transportation was provided by four galleys lent by the Knights of St.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] At Monreale, he conducted a diocesan synod.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He resigned the diocese on 9 December 1573.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 7 October 1571, the Battle of Lepanto took place in the Gulf of Corinth.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Christian fleet, commanded by King Philip II's half-brother, Don John of Austria, inflicted a decisive defeat on the Ottoman Turks, destroying all but thirty of its ships.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Farnese was on the docks at Civitavecchia to welcome home the hero, his brother's brother-in-law.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] One of the determining factors in the minds of the electors was the recent Battle of Lepanto (7 October 1571).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] It had been a stunning defeat for the Ottoman Turks, the first naval defeat in more than a century, and nearly their entire navy was destroyed.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] But they did not lose control over the Eastern Mediterranean, and they were already rebuilding their navy at lightning speed.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In some people's minds, what was needed was a pope who could hold the various forces together: a Crusading pope who would also be generous with Church money to finance the war.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The new pope must also be a strong and strict defender of the Faith in the face of unorthodoxy and one who would enforce the decrees of the Council of Trent (1545–1547; 1551–1552; 1562–1563).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] There were other problems that a pope would have to face.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Queen Elizabeth I of England had been excommunicated by Pius V, and she had obtained possession of Mary, Queen of Scots.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Mary's relatives, the Guises, were the leaders of the devout hyper-Catholic party in France, who were eager for a show-down with the Huguenots.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] **Catherine de' Medici** was attempting to avoid a civil war in France, and she believed that the marriage of her daughter Margot with Henri of Navarre, a Protestant, might avert disaster but dispensations would be required of the pope.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] She was also trying to tempt Queen Elizabeth into marriage with her son, Henri, and that would require papal cooperation as well.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Her choice was the Cardinal of Ferrara, Ippolito d'Este, who was as disliked in 1572 as he had been in 1549.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] His collection of enemies had grown to include Cardinals Bonelli, Borromeo, Farnese, Medici, and Morone.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Catherine, however, was in contact with her cousin, Cosimo I, Grand Duke of Tuscany, who, behind the scenes, was promoting Cardinal Boncompagni.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal de' Medici was to inform the leaders of the Faction of Pius IV, Borromeo and Altemps, that the Medici were interested only in Sirleto and Boncompagni.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] With the French and Florentine votes, in fact, Cardinal d'Este had the resources to block any candidate he pleased (the 'virtual veto').
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The cardinals of Pius V (some twelve or thirteen votes) were joined with many of those of Pius IV to prevent the election of d'Este, but also of Farnese, Ricci, and Burali d' Arezzo.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Giovanni Morone was also a candidate again, but Cardinal Bonelli (Alessandrino, the nephew of Pius V) was prepared to use his votes to exclude him.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] His friends nonetheless made an effort to have him elected by acclamation on the opening day of the Conclave, 12 May, but the attempt failed.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Farnese believed that this was his conclave, and he was making every effort to win supporters.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He knew, however, that the Spanish were against him.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On the night of the opening of the Conclave, Cardinal Granvelle arrived from Naples.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He had been sent to Italy by Philip II in 1571 to prepare the fleet which eventually met the Turks at Lepanto; he was kept on as Viceroy of Naples.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Shortly after his entry into the Conclave, he produced an unopened letter which (he said) had reached him while he was on the highway from Naples.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Granvelle opened the letter in Cardinal Farnese's presence and read the contents, which ordered Granvelle to advise Farnese that he was not to attempt to become pope "this time"—it should be remembered that, experienced as he was, Cardinal Farnese was only fifty-one.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Farnese's chances ended on the first day of the Conclave.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was acceptable to Cardinal Borromeo and the reformers.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was a successful nuncio in Spain, and was acceptable to the Spanish faction, which included Naples.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Conclave turned out to be a very short one.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 14 May, Ugo Boncompagni was elected pope, and took the name Gregory XIII.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was crowned by Cardinal Ippolito d'Este, the senior Cardinal Deacon, on 20 May 1572.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal d'Este, one of Alessandro Farnese's favorite enemies, died on 2 December 1572.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In the Spring of 1585, an embassy from Japan was making its way to Rome.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] They arrived by ship at Livorno on 1 March, and proceeded by land through Tuscany.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] They were received in Florence by the Grand Duke Francesco de' Medici.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] They proceeded on to Rome, accompanied by Cardinal Francesco Gambara, and were received with a grand show of hospitality at Caprarola by Cardinal Alessandro Farnese.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Accompanied by Gambara and Farnese, the embassy reached Rome on 22 March.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Pope Gregory XIII died after thirteen years on the Throne of Peter on 10 April 1585.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] There were sixty-two living cardinals, but only thirty-two managed to make it to Rome in time for the opening ceremonies of the Conclave on Easter Sunday, 21 April 1585.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Farnese, though he was only sixty-four years old, was the senior cardinal present.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was both Dean of the Sacred College of Cardinals and Cardinal Bishop of Ostia.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Thirty-nine cardinals, many of them his friends and supporters, had died during the reign of Gregory XIII.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] There was only one other cardinal present who had been created by his grandfather, Paul III.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Imperial-Spanish faction was headed by Cardinal Ferdinando de' Medici, brother of the Grand Duke of Tuscany, and soon to become the Grand Duke himself.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The actual Spanish leader was Cardinal Ludovico Madruzzo but he did not arrive in Rome until the evening of 23 April.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The French faction was headed by Ludovico d'Este, grandson of Louis XII and Protector of France before the Holy See.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] After the first vote, on 23 April, it was obvious that neither a strong Spanish candidate nor a strong French candidate could be elected.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Medici and d'Este met, and Medici proposed two possible compromise candidates to d'Este: Cardinal Albani and Cardinal Felice Peretti Montalto.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Madruzzo's chosen candidate was Cardinal Sirleto, but in a meeting with d'Este shortly after he entered the Conclave on the 24th, it was made clear to him that Sirleto was being excluded by the votes of the French.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Madruzzo declared that he would not accept Albani.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] D'Este met with Cardinal Farnese, hoping to stop any effort that Farnese might begin to exclude Montalto.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He had already been trying to organize some of Gregory XIII's cardinals into a faction of his own.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Farnese already believed that Montalto had little real support, and d'Este encouraged that misapprehension.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] But, when all the likely votes were tallied, it seemed that the supporters of Montalto lacked four votes, which would have to come from Farnese.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] When the Cardinals assembled to begin the balloting, d'Este suddenly intervened and announced that it was not necessary to proceed to a ballot since they already had a pope—Cardinal Montalto.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The cardinals immediately proceeded to "adore" Montalto—which was a legitimate method for electing a pope.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] There had to be no opposition, and there was none.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Farnese had been silenced and coerced into cooperation.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In the Spring of 1586, Cardinal Farnese's young nephew Ranuccio, aged 17, came to Rome to swear allegiance for his domains of which the Church was the feudal souverain.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He made the mistake of appearing before Pope Sixtus V in armor carrying weapons, and for that horrible crime he was imprisoned in the Castel S.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] His uncle the Cardinal pleaded twice with the Pope to have him released, and finally contrived to have Ranuccio escape.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Spanish Ambassador, Olivares, invited the Castellan of the Castel S.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Angelo to dinner, while the Cardinal tricked the guards into releasing Ranuccio into his custody.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Pope was livid at having been circumvented.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The buildings that Cardinal Farnese built or restored include the Church of the Gesù in Rome, the Villa Farnese at Caprarola, and the Farnese palace near Lake Bracciano, and the monastery Tre Fontane.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Alessandro Farnese is remembered for gathering the greatest collection of Roman sculpture assembled in private hands since Antiquity, now mostly in Naples, after passing by inheritance to the Bourbon-Parma kings.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] His generosity towards artists made a virtual academy at the house he built at Caprarola, and in his lodgings at Palazzo della Cancellaria and, after his brother Cardinal Ranuccio Farnese died in 1565, at the Palazzo Farnese.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In the Palazzo Farnese the best sculptors worked under his eye, to restore fragments of antiquities as complete sculptures, with great scholarly care.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was also a great patron of living artists including, most notably, El Greco.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Under the direction of his curator and librarian, the antiquarian iconographer Fulvio Orsini, the Farnese collections were enlarged and systematized.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Farnese collected ancient coins and commissioned modern medals.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He had paintings by Titian, Michelangelo, and Raphael, and an important collection of drawings.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He commissioned the masterpiece of Giulio Clovio, arguably the last major illuminated manuscript, the *Farnese Hours,* which was completed in 1546 after being nine years in the making (now the property of the Morgan Library, New York).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The studiolo built to house this collection appears to be the one re-erected at the Musée de la Renaissance, Écouen.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In 1550, Farnese acquired a northern portion of Palatine Hill in Rome and had Roman ruins from the palace built by the Roman Emperor Tiberius (A.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] 14–37) at the northwest end filled in, and converted to a summer home and formal gardens.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The Farnese Gardens became one of the first botanical gardens in Europe.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] From these gardens are derived the names of Acacia farnesiana and, from its floral essence, the important biochemical farnesol.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Alessandro Farnese had a daughter Clelia Farnese, with Claude de Beaune de Semblançay, dame de Châteaubrun, a lady-in-waiting and confidante of Catherine de Medicis, born in 1556.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Claude de Beaune's brother Martin became Bishop of Puy (1557–1561) and her other brother, Renaud, Bishop of Mende (1571–1581) and then Archbishop of Bourges.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In 1570, Clelia married Giangiorgio Cesarini, Marchese of Civitanova, Gonfaloniere of the City of Rome (1565–1585).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] In September 1572, they had a son, Giuliano.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 2 August 1587, at the Farnese palace in Caprarola, she married her second husband, Marco Pio di Savoia, Lord of Sassuolo; the marriage was without issue.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The absence of scandal concerning her birth suggests that Cardinal Farnese was not yet in Holy Orders ca.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Alessandro Farnese wrote a will in 1580, and added codicils in 1585, but these were revoked and replaced by a new will, written on 22 June 1588, with codicils added in July and August.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 7 July 1588, the physician of the Duke of Urbino, Vincenzo Remosetti, was summoned to a consultation at the Farnese Palace at Caprarola, "*per uno grande accidente di epilepsia"*, accompanied by severe respiratory problems.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was subjected to the usual quackery, cautery and bleeding.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Camillo Caetani, the brother of Cardinal Enrico Caetani, who kept his brother informed of Farnese's condition.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 13 August, the doctor had to return to Rome; he left the Cardinal restless and weak, and suffering from gout in his left arm.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] On 28 February 1589, he suffered an attack of some sort, perhaps a stroke.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Cardinal Farnese died quietly of the effects of apoplexy in Rome on 2 March 1589, at the age of sixty eight.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] He was buried before the high altar in the Church of the Gesù.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] Forty-two cardinals participated in the funeral ceremonies.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] commemorating the establishment of the Jesuit Order by Paul III in 1540, and the building of the Church of the Gesù for them through the generosity of Cardinal Farnese.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alessandro-farnese-cardinal] The church, the work of Giacomo Vignola and Giacomo della Porta (1568–1575), is one of the great monuments of Counter-Reformation religious architecture.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Farnese was regarded by contemporaries and historians as the greatest general of his age, as well as one of the best in history, for his talents as a commander, strategist and diplomat.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] He held a high leadership over the soldiers and mercenaries of varied nationalities which composed the Spanish *tercios*, including Spaniards, Italians, Germans and Walloons.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] His campaigns marked Spain's greatest successes in the Eighty Years' War, giving the Spanish crown permanent control of the southern provinces, in the process establishing the cultural and religious separation which would eventually become the nation of Belgium.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] During the French Wars of Religion, he decisively relieved Paris for the Catholic League, and also intervened in the Cologne War, granting victory to Ernest of Bavaria.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] He was slated to direct the land invasion of the British isles in the maligned 1588 Spanish Armada, which failed to embark him and his Army of Flanders.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] British historian Edward Shepherd Creasy wrote about him: "happy it is for England and the world that this island was saved from becoming an arena for the exhibition of his powers".
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Alessandro, born 27 August 1545, was the son of Duke Ottavio Farnese of Parma (a grandson of Pope Paul III) and Margaret of Austria (an illegitimate daughter of the Holy Roman Emperor and king of Spain Charles V).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] He had a twin brother, Carlo, who died in Rome on 7 October 1549.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] He and his mother, the half-sister of Philip II of Spain and Don Juan, left Rome for Parma in 1550.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] When Margaret was appointed Governor of the Netherlands, Alessandro accompanied her to Brussels in 1556 and was delivered to Philip II to ensure the loyalty of the Farnese.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] While in the King's custody, he visited the English royal court and then went to Spain to be raised and educated with his cousin, the ill-fated Don Carlos and his half-uncle, Don Juan, both of whom were about the same age as himself.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] In 1565 his marriage with Maria of Portugal, which ended his stint as Philip II's hostage, was celebrated in Brussels with great splendour.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] He commanded three galleys during the Battle of Lepanto (1571) and the subsequent campaigns against the Turks.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] It was seven years before he again had the opportunity to display his great military talents.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] During that time the provinces of the Netherlands had revolted against Spanish rule.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Don Juan, who had been sent as governor-general to restore order, found difficulties in dealing with William the Silent, who had succeeded in uniting all the provinces in common resistance to King Philip II.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] In the autumn of 1577 shortly after his wife's death, Farnese led Spanish reinforcements from Italy along the Spanish Road to join Don Juan, and it was his able strategy and prompt decision at a critical moment that decisively won the Battle of Gembloux in early 1578.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Shortly thereafter was the Siege of Zichem (Dutch) where the garrison was put to the sword and the town was sacked.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] This incident is considered to be the biggest stain on Farnese's otherwise chivalrous career.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Next was the five-day Siege of Nivelles (Dutch) (French) in March 1578.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The example of Zichem encouraged the citizens to capitulate so quickly.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] That summer, Farnese managed to prevent the defeat at the Battle of Rijmenam from being decisive.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] In October 1578, Don Juan, whose health had broken down, died.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Phillip II appointed Farnese to take his place as Captain-General of the Army of Flanders and appointed his mother Margaret as Governor-General.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] This was unacceptable to Alexander; he demanded to be both Captain-General and Governor-General or he would resign thus leaving military matters entirely in Margaret's hands.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Philip eventually capitulated and after four years, Margaret returned to Parma.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Upon Don Juan's death, Farnese was confronted with a difficult situation.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Perceiving that his opponents were divided between Catholic and Protestant, Fleming and Walloon, he skillfully worked to exploit these divisions.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] By this means, he regained the allegiance of the Walloon provinces for the king.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Through the treaty of Arras, January 1579, he secured the support of the "Malcontents" (the Catholic nobles of the south) for the royal cause.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The rebels in the seven northern provinces then formed the Union of Utrecht, formally abjuring Phillip's rule and pledging to fight to the end.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] As soon as he had secured a base of operations in Hainaut and Artois, Farnese set himself in earnest to the task of reconquering Brabant and Flanders by force of arms, beginning with Maastricht.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Farnese commenced the Siege of Maastricht on 12 March 1579.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The inhabitants of Maastricht were also digging to reach the Spanish tunnels.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Deep underground the fighting continued, hundreds of Spanish soldiers died as boiling oil was poured into their tunnels.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Others died because of a lack of oxygen when the Dutch defenders ignited fires within them.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Another 500 Spanish soldiers died when a mine, which they planned to use to blow up the wall, exploded prematurely.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] On the night of 29 June, Farnese's men managed to get into the city while the exhausted defenders were asleep.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Since the city had not surrendered after the walls had been breached, laws of warfare in the 16th century gave the victors the right to loot the conquered city.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The Spanish looted the city for three days during which time many civilians lost their lives.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The looting was particularly violent, perhaps because Farnese was in bed with a fever during those three days.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] In adherence to the treaty of Arras, the Spanish troops were expelled from the country so Alexander only had the Walloon troops available for the Siege of Tournai (Dutch).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The difficulties encountered with the ragtag troops during that siege helped convince the Walloon lords to allow for the return of foreign, more importantly, Spanish troops.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] In a war composed mostly of sieges rather than battles, Parma proved his mettle.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] His strategy was to offer generous terms for surrender: there would be no massacres or looting; historic urban privileges were retained; there was a full pardon and amnesty; return to the Catholic Church would be gradual.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The apex of Alexander Farnese's career was when he laid siege to the great seaport of Antwerp.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The town was open to the sea, strongly fortified, and defended with resolute determination and courage by its citizens.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The latter were led by the famous Marnix van St.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Aldegonde and assisted by an ingenious Italian engineer named Federigo Giambelli.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The siege began in 1584 and called forth all of Farnese's military genius.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] He cut off all access to Antwerp from the sea by constructing a bridge of boats across the Scheldt from Kallo (then spelt *Calloo*) to Oordam, in spite of the desperate efforts of the besieged townspeople.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The terms offered included the clause that all Protestants had to leave the city within four years.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] This disciplined capture and occupation of the town should not be confused with the bloody events of the Spanish Fury on 4 November 1576.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Farnese avoided the mistakes of his predecessors including Don Luis de Requesens.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] With the Fall of Antwerp, and with Mechelen and Brussels already in the hands of Farnese, the whole of the southern Netherlands was once more placed under the authority of Philip II.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Both Holland and Zeeland, whose geographical position made them unassailable except by water, were hard-pressed to retain the territory.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Alexander pressed operations in the regions of the Meuse and the Rhine so as to maintain trade with Germany and prepare a gateway for winning Holland and Zeeland.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Unfortunately for the prince, Phillip II's parsimonious disbursement of money started having its effect in the campaigns following Antwerp's conquest.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The first notable Spanish defeat under Farnese's command came at his first attempt to take control of Grave.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] In December 1585, with the growing food shortage, Farnese marched his troops towards the Rhine and Meuse regions so as to spare Flanders, Brabant and the Walloon provinces the burden of feeding them and, while there, undertake operations to secure trade along those rivers.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] That winter was nearly disastrous for Farnese's army were it not for the "Miracle of Empel".
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Nevertheless, by 7 June the Siege of Grave (1586) was a fait accompli.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] On the other hand, fortunately for Alexander, who became Duke upon his father's death in 1586, the poorly supplied English forces, sent by Elizabeth I, were duly defeated by the Duke's forces.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The Siege of Sluis (1587) was necessary, so as to secure a safe harbour for the Armada ships, and was successful.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] When Alexander Farnese became Duke of Parma through the death of his father; he never ruled, instead naming his son Ranuccio as regent.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] He applied for leave to visit his paternal territory but Philip II would not grant it as there were no suitable candidates in the Netherlands to replace him.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] However, while retaining him in his command at the head of a formidable army, the king would not give his sanction to his great general's desire to use it for the conquest of England, at the time a supporter of the rebels.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Philip overruled him and solicited the Marquis of Santa Cruz to draft and present an invasion plan called the *Enterprise of England*, more commonly known as the Spanish Armada.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] As part of the general campaign preparations, Farnese moved against Ostend and Sluis, the latter of which would be taken on August 1587.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The plan was that Parma's troops would cross the channel in barges, protected by the Armada.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Santa Cruz was appointed commander of the armada but died in early 1588 and command of the armada was given to the incompetent Duke of Medina Sidonia.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The Armada entered the English Channel in the summer of that year but poor communication between Parma and the Armada's commander made effective coordination difficult.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Alexander informed Philip II that his barges were nothing more than flat-bottomed transport vessels, not warships, and he was being blockaded by English ships thus preventing him from leaving Nieuwpoort and Dunkirk.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Farnese expected the Armada to clear a passage for his barges.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Parma's troops were also threatened by the presence of Dutch forces in flyboats, who hoped to destroy the barges and drown Parma's army at sea.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] In contrast, Medina Sidonia expected Parma to fight his way out from the ports and meet him in the channel.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The English attack on the Armada in the Battle of Gravelines (1588), followed by an unfavourable change in wind direction, made link-up impossible.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] After the failure of the Armada, fortune seems to have abandoned the Duke of Parma.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Farnese broke up his camp in Dunkirk in September and sent the Marquis de Renty to the island of Tholen in preparation to besiege the predominately English garrison at Bergen Op Zoom.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Renty did not succeed in capturing Tholen, blaming bad weather, whereupon Farnese expressed that he should have led the expedition personally.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Nevertheless, on 19 September 1588, Alexander set out from Bruges with his army to besiege Bergen Op Zoom.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] After a six-week siege, with winter approaching, Parma abandoned the enterprise and withdrew to Brussels, sending his troops into winter quarters.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Alexander's final major victory in the Netherlands was Geertruidenberg, a strategic gateway to Holland.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The English garrison there was in full revolt for lack of pay.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] An English representative offered the city to Parma and it was ultimately delivered to him on 9 April 1589.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The Duke of Parma started feeling the first effects of oedema after the failed siege of Bergen op Zoom.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] He had to go to the town of Spa to treat his illness for nearly six months.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] During this time, the Old Tercio of Lombardy had mutinied and Farnese ordered that it be dissolved.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Following this incident, Alexander's lieutenants suffered defeats in Friesland and Rheinberg.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] This enabled the Dutch rebels to regain momentum in their revolt, which had been in ever deeper trouble since 1576.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Parma had warned Philip II that the French incursion would endanger the gains made in the Netherlands and stated he would not accept responsibility for the losses or failures resulting from not heeding his advice.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Parma left Brussels on 6 August 1590 and ultimately arrived at Guise on 15 August.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] In late August, he moved to relieve Paris from the lengthy siege it had been placed under by Huguenots and Royalists loyal to Henry IV.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Farnese's main goal was simply to resupply Paris by raising the blockade, not obliterating Henry's army.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] When Henry learned of the approach of Mayenne and Farnese, he broke camp to actively engage in battle.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Parma had no intention of engaging in combat.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] He determined that capturing the fort at Lagny-sur-Marne would ensure traffic was maintained along the river Marne which was still in the hands of the Catholic League.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] At dawn on 5 September, Lagny was bombarded then stormed by Spanish troops who put its 800-man garrison to the sword, all within sight of Henri's camp, a mere 12 km away.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The latter abandoned the siege of Paris two days later but made one last "Hail Mary" attempt on 8–9 September which failed.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] With the course of the Marne completely open to traffic, supplies flowed into Paris for the next several days.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Keeping Paris supplied required the influx of victuals from multiple sources but most of Henri's forces occupied the areas along the Seine and Yonne rivers so Parma decided to clear Corbeil in order to restore traffic on the Seine.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The siege began on 22 September and by 16 October, the town was taken.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Its garrison was put to the sword and the town was thoroughly sacked.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] With the siege of Paris lifted and its supply routes secured, Farnese took the road on 3 November back to the Netherlands, where Maurice of Nassau had gone on the offensive.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Alexander's withdraw was not an easy one.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] He had thousands of men, wagons and horses to move during foul weather with the Béarnaise harassing him the entire way.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Anticipating these difficulties, the Duke arranged his columns in such a way that Henri could not rout him.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Twenty days into the march, on 25 November near Amiens, Henri with his cavalry boldly charged Farnese's column only to himself be routed beyond the river Aisne and getting wounded during the retreat.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] One final unsuccessful skirmish took place on 29 November where Henri was within a few hundred paces of Farnese.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Parma and Mayenne parted ways at Guise and Alexander arrived in Brussels on 4 December 1590.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Alexander Farnese had appointed Peter Ernst von Mansfeld as acting Governor-General while he was in France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Days after Farnese's departure for France, Mansfeld and Colonel Francisco Verdugo, operating in Friesland, began lamenting to Philip II about the lack of money, supplies, and troop mutinies, all the things Farnese had been complaining about for the past several years.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] By the time Farnese had returned, Maurice had regained Steenbergen, Roosendaal, Oosterhout, Turnhout, and Westerlo.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Farnese's absence brought with it a reduction in military activity on the part of the Spanish thus allowing the Dutch some time to reflect on what policies they needed to adopt that would be most effective against their enemy.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] This was the beginning of the Dutch Military Reforms which finally allowed them to have an even footing against the Spanish; Alexander had finally met his match in Maurice, the Prince of Orange.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] On the night of 24 July 1591, just days after engaging in the siege of Knodsenburg, Alexander Farnese received orders from Philip II to drop everything and go back to France to aid the Catholic League.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Realizing the difficulties of capturing this fort, he was actually relieved to be able to honourably abandon this enterprise engaged under bad auspices.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Before he could even consider another expedition to aid the League, he needed to resume his treatments at Spa whence he arrived on 1 August with his son Ranuccio.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] In mid-November, Alexander drafted instructions for the interim Governor-General, Mansfeld again, in addition to putting measures in place for the defence of the Netherlands while he was away.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] By the end of November, the Duke was in Valenciennes where he mustered his troops.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Towards the middle of January 1592, Parma had rendezvoused with Mayenne and made preparations to rescue Rouen from Henri.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Before heading to Rouen, Farnese made the strategic decision to capture Neufchâtel-en-Bray.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Finally, on 20 April, Parma arrived a few miles from Rouen where he was met by 50 cavalry sent by Villars.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] They informed him that Henri had lifted the siege and withdrew in the direction of Pont-de-l'Arche to entrench there.; Rouen was saved.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Rather than follow Farnese's advice and attack Henri's camp and destroy his forces, the League's leaders chose to capture Caudebec-en-Caux where he was subsequently wounded by a musket shot in the right forearm during the siege whilst reconnoitring the town.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The wound undermined his already precarious health even more and he was forced to call his son Ranuccio to take command of the troops.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Henri saw therein an opportunity to avenge the loss of Rouen.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Rather than risk a full attack against the League's forces, he took a page from Farnese's book and decided to cut off all supply routes and starve them.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The League's army abandoned Caudebec for Yvetot.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The situation was worse than at Caudebec, all the while, Farnese was seriously ill and mostly bed-ridden yet still sharp in mind.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The Duke of Parma finally devised a plan to clandestinely cross the Seine in boats leaving just enough men to make Henri believe the entire army was encamped.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The Catholic army was across the river and long gone by the time Henri learned of it, literally right under his nose.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] After returning to the Netherlands, Alexander received a letter from Pope Clement VIII on 28 June congratulating him “for rescuing the Catholic Army.” Farnese quickly made his way back to Spa for yet more treatments.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Ever since the failed armada campaign against England, Spanish agents and courtiers in Philip II's court who were jealous of Farnese's success had been engaged in a malicious campaign to discredit the Duke of Parma in the eyes of the king.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] After Farnese's return from his second French campaign, the king, who had always favoured his nephew Alexander, allowed these complaints and accusations to influence his opinion.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] This change in sentiment caused the king to order the duke removed from his post in the Netherlands.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The sovereign drafted a recall letter on 20 February 1592, while Farnese was marching on Rouen, and tasked Juan Pacheco de Toledo, II marqués de Cerralbo, to personally deliver it to the duke upon his return to Flanders.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The king then assigned Pedro Henriquez de Acevedo, Count of Fuentes to carry out this mission.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The date of the recall letter was changed to 28 June 1592.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Given Philip II's nature toward duplicitous intrigue, the king reassured Farnese that everything was fine, all the while arranging for his recall from Flanders.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The duke knew nothing about these machinations and by October was feeling well enough to return to Brussels only to learn that he was ordered to aid the League yet again.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Fully aware of his state of health, the Duke of Parma, nevertheless, prepared for this campaign by arranging for loans and sumptuous quarters in Paris so as to give the appearance of a powerful representative of the King of Spain.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] He had written his last will and testament, repeatedly went to confession and took holy communion, and sent his son back to Parma so that, upon his death, the Farnesian States would not be deprived of a ruler.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] The duke left Brussels on 11 November, arriving in Arras where, on 2 December 1592, he died at the age of 47.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] His mortal remains were dressed in a Capuchin habit, moved to Parma and buried in the Capuchin church, next to his wife's tomb.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Later, their mortal remains were moved to the crypt of the Basilica of the Madonna della Steccata, where they are still found today.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] His death spared him from seeing the provision by which he was relieved of the post of Governor-General.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] In January 2020, the Duke's remains were exhumed in a bid to clarify the circumstances of his death which were ultimately determined to be pneumonia.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Historian Edward Shepherd Creasy regarded Farnese as "one of the most formidable generals that ever could be placed at the head of an army designed not only to win battles, but to effect conquests" due to his combination of military talent and political wisdom.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Others authors similarly cite him as the first general of his age.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Historian John Keegan extolled Farnese's military skill and his conjunction of "Italian cunning... and love of battle".
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Garrett Mattingly also praised his ability to fluidly coordinate the many nationalities and allegiances of the Spanish armies.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] His name is commemorated in the modern Tercio Alejandro Farnesio No.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Farnese was esteemed even by his Protestants adversaries for his success and charisma, as well as his good faith with the vanquished.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] He found his only rival in Maurice of Nassau, who Keegan considered probably inferior to Farnese.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Farnese's campaigns are considered the original source of the separation between the modern nations of Belgium and the Netherlands.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Alessandro Farnese had an affair with Françoise de Renty (a.k.a., "La Belle Franchine"), a young Flemish noblewoman, confirmed by an unpublished letter of instruction from Parma, contained in the manuscript at the Bibliotecca Nazionale di Napoli, Brancacciani F1, ff.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Although there is nothing to say with certainty about children from this relationship, according to Bertini, Farnese arranged for, and gave incentives to, Count Jean-Charles de Gavre, a nobleman in Alessandro's household, to marry Françoise in 1586.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma] Considering that the couple's first child, Marie-Alexandrine-Françoise de Gavre, was born soon afterwards in 1587, that her name (Alexandrine) is not found amongst either parent's ancestors, and the influence Françoise had over Farnese, it is quite possible that he was the child's biological father.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-prince-of-parma] He is not to be confused with his better-known great-grandfather Alexander Farnese, Duke of Parma.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-prince-of-parma] This Alessandro was often called **Alessandro di Odoardo** (son of Odoardo).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-prince-of-parma] His elder brother Ranuccio II was the sixth duke of Parma and Piacenza .
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-prince-of-parma] He was born in Parma, the second son of Odoardo Farnese, fifth duke of Parma, and Margherita de' Medici.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-prince-of-parma] He was general in the army of Venice, fighting the Turks, and later admiral in the Spanish Navy.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alexander-farnese-prince-of-parma] He became governor of the Southern Netherlands after the Franco-Dutch War.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] He was one of the wealthiest men in Europe and a patron of the arts.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Successful for his prodigious logistic ability, he organized naval defense and commerce in the southern Iberian Peninsula, managing fleets and pioneering the usage of vessels like frigates.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Despite this, he was not personally a naval commander, which contributed to the failure of the Spanish Armada, entrusted to him against his judgement.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] His defective performance during the battle marked his career in late historiography.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Alonso's father was Juan Carlos Pérez de Guzmán, who died in 1556.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] This was two years before the death of his own father, Juan Alfonso Pérez de Guzmán, 6th Duke of Medina Sidonia, meaning that Juan Carlos failed to inherit the ducal title and died merely as the 9th Count of Niebla.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] His paternal grandmother, who died in 1528, was Ana de Aragón y de Gurrea, an illegitimate daughter of Alonso de Aragón y Ruiz de Iborra, Archbishop of Zaragoza, himself an illegitimate son of king Ferdinand II of Aragón.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] In 1518 Ana de Aragón had married in succession two Dukes of Medina Sidonia.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] The first marriage was to Alfonso Pérez de Guzmán, 5th Duke of Medina Sidonia, who was to die childless in 1548.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] He was declared insane ("mentecato"), which invalidated the marriage and vacated the succession to the title.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] The bride was then married, in the same year, to the 5th Duke's brother, Juan Alfonso, the 6th Duke, born on 24 March 1502.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] He would survive his bride by three decades, dying at Sanlúcar de Barrameda, in the province of Cádiz, Spain, on 26 November, 1558.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] As Alonso's father, Juan Carlos, had already died in 1556, it was on the death of his grandfather in 1559, that Alonso, only some nine years of age at the time, inherited the ducal title along with one of the greatest fortunes in Europe.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] The 7th duke was betrothed in 1569 to Ana de Silva y Mendoza, who was then four years of age, the daughter of the Prince and the Princess of Éboli.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] In 1572 when the duchess was little more than ten years of age, the pope granted a dispensation for the consummation of the marriage.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] The Duke of Medina Sidonia had a son, Juan Manuel, who succeeded his father.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] A scandal of the time accused Philip II of a love intrigue with the young girl's mother, the Princess of Éboli.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] The constant unvarying and apparently unmotivated favor the king showed the duke has been accounted for by claiming he simply took a fatherly interest in the girl.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] In any case no proof has been discovered of any relation between the king and the princess.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Don Alonso made no serious effort to save his mother-in-law Ana de Mendoza, Princess of Éboli from the later persecution she suffered at the hands of Philip II.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] His correspondence is full of whining complaints of poverty, and appeals to the king for pecuniary favors.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] In 1581 he was created a knight of the Golden Fleece, and was named Captain General of Lombardy.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] By pressing supplications to the king he got himself exempted on the ground of poverty and poor health.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Don Alonso was also the patron of Don Jerónimo Sánchez de Carranza who wrote the premier text on the Spanish system of swordplay which was called the 'True Art' or the *Verdadera Destreza*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] He was asked by King Philip II of Spain to lead the Spanish Armada.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] When the Marquis of Santa Cruz died, on 9 February 1588, Philip insisted on appointing the 7th Duke to the command of the Armada.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] He had prepared his orders to the Duke of Medina Sidonia already three days before the death of Santa Cruz.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] The motivation of Philip's decision is unknown, but it may have been grounded in his consideration of the duke's very high social rank, administrative competence, modesty and tactfulness, and last but not least his reputation as a good Catholic.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] The micro-managing king probably wanted a commander who would obey his instructions to the letter, which had been less likely had command been in the hands of Santa Cruz, or either of the most experienced officers in the Armada, Juan Martinez de Recalde and Miguel de Oquendo.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Philip II may never have seen this letter, for his secretaries Don Juan de Idiaquez and Don Cristobal de Moura replied to the duke that they dared not show it to the king.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Even though the king did or did not read the Medina Sidonia's letter, Philip himself was confident that there were no issues.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] As the king himself was a devout Catholic, he was certain that God would favor the Armada as a means to punish the English for their Protestant heresy and restore them and Dutch to the One True Faith.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] After all, he had secured a blessing from Pope Sixtus V a papal blessing, which was given somewhat reluctantly.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Historians have speculated that Medina Sidonia himself did not believe in the success of the Armada, and that this motivated his attempt to reject the command as also a later letter he wrote to the king, advising an attempt to conclude peace or at least postpone the operation.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] What general opinion of the duke may have been is unrecorded, but it is known that skepticism regarding the Armada's prospects existed among senior Spanish officers and informed foreign commentators.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] The opinion of modern historians on Medina Sidonia's efforts to prepare the Armada is generally favorable.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] He reorganized the fleet, rationalized the chaotic distribution of loads and guns, and increased the ammunition supplies from 30 to 50 rounds per gun.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] The permission of the king to add the Castilian galleons of the "Indian Guard" to the Armada nearly doubled its first-line fighting strength.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Under the duke's command the material state of the Armada and the manning of the ships was much improved.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Medina Sidonia managed to establish good relationships with his subordinate commanders, and gathered additional supplies right up to the moment of sailing.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Medina Sidonia's behavior as a fleet commander in the ensuing series of fights with the English has come under more criticism.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Lacking military experience, he showed little initiative or self-confidence, instead cautiously obeying the instructions of the king, and relying on the opinion of his advisers and subordinate commanders.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] This tendency was reinforced by the senior adviser appointed to him by the king, Diego Flores de Valdes, an experienced sea officer but also a man renowned for his caution.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Medina Sidonia also seriously underestimated the difficulty of coordinating his actions with the commander of the Spanish forces in the Netherlands, Alexander Farnese, Duke of Parma, who was supposed to launch his invasion fleet to meet the Armada at sea.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] However, this problem was fundamental to the operational plan imposed on the two commanders by Philip II.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Allowing for the limitations inherent in a total lack of command experience, Medina Sidonia fought the battle courageously and intelligently.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] His health suffered badly as a result of the campaign, and after his return to Spain the king finally relieved him of his command and granted him permission to return home to convalesce.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Later, he served the Spanish crown for another two decades in various functions.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] The duke's reputation suffered, because several popular accounts, notably the one written by the monk Juan de Victoria, placed all blame for the defeat on him.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Informed commentators and modern historians have put most of the blame on Philip II himself for imposing an impractical plan on his commanders, and on Diego Flores de Valdes for badly advising the duke.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] Philip II himself did not single out his chosen commander to bear the responsibility for the defeat.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] He stated "Action without cause is illegitimate of reason" in response to public outcry on re-sending a fleet to Britain.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] The duke retained his posts of admiral of the ocean and captain-general of Andalusia, and continued to serve Philip II and later Philip III.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] The popular image of the duke in later years was strongly influenced by propaganda surrounding the Armada, including an English account which claimed that the Duke of Medina Sidonia was a fool and a coward who hid below decks in a specially reinforced room.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] This story became a lasting part of popular descriptions of the battle, in which the Duke of Medinia Sidonia was frequently portrayed as an incompetent buffoon.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] When an English fleet attacked Cádiz in 1596, Medina Sidonia's allegedly slow response was blamed for giving the English enough time to sack the city.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] In 1606 Medina Sidonia's obstinacy caused the loss of a squadron which was destroyed near Gibraltar by the Dutch.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/alonso-de-guzmán-y-sotomayor-7th-duke-of-medina-sidonia] This episode made the duke a satirical target of Miguel de Cervantes.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The town was fought over during both World Wars, suffering significant damage, and was repeatedly occupied by both sides.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The 1918 Battle of Amiens was the opening phase of the Hundred Days Offensive which directly led to the Armistice with Germany.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Royal Air Force heavily bombed the town during the Second World War.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] In the aftermath, the city was rebuilt according to Pierre Dufau's plans with wider streets to ease traffic congestion.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] These newer structures were primarily built of brick, concrete and white stone with slate roofs.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The architect Auguste Perret designed the Gare d'Amiens train station and nearby Tour Perret.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Amiens has an important historical and cultural heritage, on which a significant amount of tourism is based.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Apart from the cathedral, there are the hortillonnages, the Jules Verne House, the Tour Perret, the Musée de Picardie, the zoo, and the Saint-Leu and Saint-Maurice neighborhoods.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] A total of 60 monuments are listed in the inventory of monuments historiques, over 1600 places and monuments listed in the general inventory of cultural heritage, and 187 objects listed in the inventory of monuments historiques.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] During December, the town hosts the largest Christmas market in northern France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The first known settlement at this location was **Samarobriva** ("Somme bridge"), the central settlement of the Ambiani tribe, one of the principal tribes of Gaul.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Romans named the town Ambianum, meaning settlement of the Ambiani people.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Amiens was part of Francia starting from the 5th century.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Normans sacked the city in 859 and again in 882.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] In 1113, the city was recognized by King Louis VI of France, and in 1185 it was linked to the Crown of France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] In 1597, Spanish soldiers held the city during the six-month Siege of Amiens, before Henry IV regained control.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] During the 18th and 19th century, the textile tradition of Amiens became famous for its velours.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] As a result of the French Revolution, the provinces of France were dismantled and the territory was organised into departments.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Much of Picardy became the newly created department of Somme with Amiens as the departmental capital.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] During the industrial revolution, the city walls were demolished, opening up space for large boulevards around the town center.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Henriville neighborhood in the south of the city was developed around this time.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] In 1848, the first railway arrived in Amiens, linking the city to Boulogne-sur-Mer.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] During the 1870 Battle of Amiens, the city was occupied by invading Prussian forces.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The town was fought over during both the First and Second World Wars, suffering significant damage and being occupied several times by both sides.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The 1918 Battle of Amiens was the opening phase of the Hundred Days Offensive which led directly to the Armistice with Germany that ended the war.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] In June 1944 following D-Day, Amiens was heavily bombed by the Royal Air Force.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The town was liberated by British forces on 31 August.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The city was rebuilt according to Pierre Dufau's plans with a focus on widening the streets to ease traffic congestion.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Amiens, once regional prefecture of the former Picardy Region, is the prefecture of the Somme department, one of the three departments (with Oise and Aisne) in the region.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Located in the Paris Basin, the city benefits from a privileged geographical position, with close proximity to Paris, Lille, Rouen, London and Brussels.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] At the crossroads of major European routes of travel (A1, A16 and A29), the city is also at the heart of a major rail star.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] As the crow flies, the city is 115 kilometres (71 mi) north of Paris, 97 kilometres (60 mi) south-west of Lille, 100 kilometres (62 mi) north-east of Rouen, 162 kilometres (101 mi) east-north-east of Le Havre and 144 kilometres (89 mi) north-west of Reims.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] At the regional level, Amiens is located 53 kilometres (33 mi) north of Beauvais, 71 kilometres (44 mi) west of Saint-Quentin, 66 kilometres (41 mi) from Compiègne and 102 kilometres (63 mi) from Laon.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] In area, Amiens is the third-largest settlement in the Somme, after Crécy-en-Ponthieu and Hornoy-le-Bourg.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The area of the commune is 4,946 hectares (12,220 acres); the altitude varies between 14 and 106 metres (46 and 348 ft).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The main stem of the River Somme passes through Amiens and is generally benign, except during exceptional floods that can last up to several weeks (such as in spring 2001).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] It is also, on its southeastern outskirts, close to Camon and Longueau, the confluence with its main tributary on the left bank (to the south), and the Avre.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The city developed in a natural narrowing of the river due to the advance of the rim of the Picard plateau in Saint-Pierre (ford crossing).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Amiens citadel is built on this limestone butte of the Picard plateau and *Rue Saint-Pierre* is a slightly inclined path to leave the city from the north.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] At this narrowing, a network of narrow canals led to the construction of bridges and buildings including textile mills in the Middle Ages.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The marshes of the old bed of the river Somme was used to dig peat.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Farmers maintained rieux, canals and ditches by cleaning out the silt and used it to append to their vegetable garden plot.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] During the 20th century maintenance of the canals was stopped and gardens were gradually left to lie fallow or sold to private individuals who created pleasure gardens accessible by boat.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The hydrographic network has always been an important city-operated asset.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The river helped shape the identity of the landscape, urban and economic territory.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] It is around the Saint-Leu and Saint-Maurice neighborhoods that border the River Somme, as well as most of the administrative and civil area of the current city center which the city has developed since antiquity.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Canal de la Somme dates from the beginning of the 19th century and the bridge at the foot of the citadel was built after World War II.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Amiens has the typical oceanic climate of the north of France, with relatively mild winters, cool summers, and rainfall well distributed throughout the year.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Amiens is a hub between the Île de France and the rest of northern France; Normandy and Benelux; and France and Great Britain.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Amiens is not directly on principal European road and rail arteries, such as the A1 motorway and the Paris-Lille TGV train line, at present.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] However, due to its position halfway between the urban areas of Lille and Paris, Amiens has good conditions for service and accessibility, including motorways (at the junction of the A16 and A29).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Amiens station is served by regional train services to destinations that include Rouen, Calais, Lille, Reims, Compiègne and Paris-Nord.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Saint-Roch (Somme) station in the western part of the city is served by local trains towards Rouen and Abbeville.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] A regular bus route with the TGV Haute-Picardie station also provides access to the Charles-de-Gaulle Airport station.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] On the horizon of 2025, the Roissy–Picardie Link will put Amiens 55 minutes from Paris Charles-de-Gaulle Airport and its TGV station.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Since antiquity, Amiens has been a crossroads of important routes.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The contemporary city is served by the A16 and A29 autoroutes.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Jules Verne Viaduct, 943 metres (3,094 ft) long, crosses the River Somme to the east of the city and allows circumvention of the city by motorway-type roads.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The A16 and A29 autoroutes, the RN1 and the RN25 form a bypass-type motorway around the city that the population has called the *Rocade d'Amiens* or Amiens ring road.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] According to the urban transport plan (PDU) approved 19 December 2013 for the period 2013–2023 parking supply is considered abundant in Amiens.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Although important, demand for parking is less than what is available (capacity reserves are still 20% minimum: If the road is sometimes saturated, the occupancy rate of the underground parking remains globally less than 100%).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] In 2013, the city counted approximately 70,000 public parking spaces, including 8,400 in the city center and in its immediate vicinity, where 70% of places are paid.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] As of 2007, a residential parking system has been deployed in Saint-Anne ward to cope with congestion in the streets caused by SNCF railway station users.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] During the campaign for the municipal election of 2008, parking was one of the important topics of debate.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] A year after the change of majority, the Gilles Demailly team launched a consultation with the population.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] From 2011, residential parking was extended to the Gare-La-Vallée and Riolan neighborhoods, then in 2012 to the Noyon neighborhood and the area east of the Riolan sector.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] In 2014, 2,600 parking spaces were affected by this system which allowed city residents more parking near their homes in order to promote a better rotation of vehicles in the streets and reduce permanent occupation of public space by the cars cluttering the highway.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Amiens was once served by two tram lines with a combined length of 10.7 kilometres (6.6 mi), opened in 1887.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] They intersected at *Place Gambetta*, one linking La Madeleine Cemetery, the Church of Saint-Acheul, Cagnard bridge, *Rue de Noyon* and *Rue Jules-Barni*; the other from the Church of Saint-Pierre at the racecourse, by the streets of Saint-Leu, Frédéric-Petit and Colbert.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Electrified in 1899, the network grew to seven lines totaling 19 kilometres (12 mi) in 1906.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] From 1932, Longueau was linked to Amiens by a bus service.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] German bombing in 1940 destroyed most of the city center and hit the Jules-Ferry Road tram depot, totally destroying the tram fleet.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] A few old Parisian buses were also used in an extremely reduced service.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] These buses as well as the surviving bus were then converted to city gas and equipped with tanks on the roof covered by a huge white dome.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] This service continued until approximately 1946.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] There were only two urban lines: An east–west line (Saint-Acheul – Montieres) and a northeast–southwest line (Beauville – road to Rouen).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] It was decided after the war to serve the city by a trolleybus with one route to Longueau.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] This was only in part realized, serving Saint-Acheul, Rouen, La Madeleine and Saint-Pierre.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] In 1964, trolleybuses were abandoned and the bus became ubiquitous in Amiens transportation.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The current public transport network consists of a bus network managed by the Ametis mixed economy company, whose network covers Amiens Métropole, the agglomeration of Amiens.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The establishment of dedicated bus lanes began in 2006.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Former Mayor Gilles de Robien had envisioned the creation of a tram, but the choice of dedicated bus lanes had been preferred for reasons of cost and patronage.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] His successor, Mayor Gilles Demailly, had been considering the development of a TSCP in the metropolitan area.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] As a result of numerous studies and conferences, elected representatives voted for the creation of a tram at the municipal Council of 15 November 2012.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The project had been endorsed by the Communauté d'agglomération Amiens Métropole on 18 December 2012 and the commissioning of a first north–south tram route was scheduled for 2018/2019.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Improvement of public transit would then be only by that of the bus network.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Indeed, in December of the same year, the Community Council approved funding for a study (the sixth in 20 years) relating to the establishment of a rapid transit bus network (BHNS), which should enter into service in March 2019, and whose vehicles could be electric.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Amiens has developed two bike services: Buscyclette and Velam.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] In 2012, Amiens Métropole had 100 kilometres (62 mi) of routes for cyclists.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Despite the development of a bicycle plan in 1997 which was planning the development of 500 kilometres (310 mi) of equipped cycleways, the network of the territory in terms of paths is still incomplete.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The blueprint of the bicycle facilities of the agglomeration (SDAC) provides, over a period of 10 years (2014–2024), for 188 kilometres (117 mi) of cycle routes and equips 490 sites for the parking of bikes.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] This plan also includes the deployment of parking facilities over the entire territory of the city, close to the facilities frequented by bikers, as well as cyclist right-turns at traffic lights or even the maintenance of existing facilities.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Connections from these two stations include to Lille via Arras and Douai, to Boulogne via Abbeville, to Paris-Nord via Creil or Compiègne, to Reims via Tergnier, and to Rouen.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Many regional and extra regional links (Normandie, Grand Est and Île-de-France) pass through Amiens, especially by TER Hauts-de-France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] A station located 45 kilometres (28 mi) from Amiens, the Haute-Picardie TGV station, allows access to the TGV network.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Its isolated character earned it the name of *gare des betteraves*, or *gare betteraves*, at the time of its construction.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] In addition to Amiens – Glisy Aerodrome, bordering the town's eastern edge 5 kilometres (3.1 mi) from the center, there are several airports nearby.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Somme canal runs through the town to the English Channel.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] This canal is linked to the Canal du Nord (Paris to Lille metropolitan area).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Amiens comprises a number of neighborhoods (French: *quartiers*) with their own characteristics, including Saint-Leu, St-Maurice, Henriville, and Saint-Acheul.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] St-Leu forms part of Amiens, north of the city center.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] It has many older wooden and brick houses and several canals.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] At the foot of the cathedral, traversed by canals, this picturesque area was largely rehabilitated during the 1990s.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] It extends to the Somme canal, located more to the north, at the foot of the Coteau Saint-Pierre on which the fortress of Jean Errard, called *Citadelle*, was built.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Historically, it was the poor neighborhood of the city, where butchers, tanners and dyers gathered.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Amiens University's Faculty of Sciences, present since the 1960s, has been renovated and expanded on occasion.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Faculty of Law and Economics has also been transferred since the mid-1990s from the campus (offset to the south of the city) to its new location at the foot of the cathedral.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The open-air parking it replaces was a "gap" in the landscape dating from World War II.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Nonetheless, it allowed an unobstructed view of the cathedral.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Most of the buildings have been renovated and transformed into housing much of which is for students.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The area became the heart of the Amiens people's evenings, with many establishments (bars, restaurants, etc.) on *Place du Don* and *Quai Bélu*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The church is found at *Rue Saint-Leu*, located just between the Faculty of Science and Law-Economy (UPJV).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Two theatres were established in the neighborhood, that of the Chés Cabotans (puppet shows in the Picard language) and the *Maison du Théâtre* at the foot of the Saint-Leu Church.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] There is also *La Lune des Pirates*, a concert hall.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Located to the west of the Citadelle, and east of the La Madeleine Cemetery, this very old working-class neighborhood of Amiens acted as an industrial center in the 18th century.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] It is currently undergoing significant housing renovation and development.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Bordered by the Canal de la Somme, it offers a stopover for leisure boats, which must go through a lock.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The walls of the city's former dye factory are now those of the École supérieure d'art et de design d'Amiens (ESAD) as well as those of the Faculty of Arts.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The École supérieure d'ingénieurs en électronique et électrotechnique (ESIEE) is in the same neighborhood.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Jardin des plantes, known as the *Jardin du Roy* within the city, is also located in this neighborhood.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Henriville neighborhood was mostly built during the 19th century after the demolition of the city wall.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] It lies at the south of the town center.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] It has numerous bourgeois houses and townhouses, predominantly in brick, blending architectural styles of the period, including neoclassical, troubadour and neo-Gothic.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] There are also private mansions, such as the Acloque mansion and the house of Jules Verne.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Saint-Acheul neighborhood (IPA: [sɛ̃t‿aʃœl]) existed before Amiens' inception, as people have lived there since prehistoric times.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] This is where archaeological excavations in the nineteenth century discovered prehistoric tool sets typical of the "Acheulean" prehistorical era, named after this neighborhood (also spelled Acheulian, pronounced [aʃœljɑ̃]).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Thr archaeological garden there is open to the public.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Not to be confused with the commune of Saint-Acheul situated 37 km (23 mi) to the north, the Saint-Acheul neighborhood is the site of a military cemetery from the First World War (1914–1918).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] It also contains the Church of Saint-Acheul, the Jesuit former Saint-Acheul College and the former normal school (teacher-training college), which became the Lycée Robert-de-Luzarches.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] A number of famous people are buried in the former Saint-Acheul cemetery, such as the creator of *Bécassine*, J.P.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Part of the neighborhood includes a so-called English neighborhood, with typical English-style houses.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] At the foot of this area lie the *hortillonnages*, a marshy area criss-crossed by canals.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] These areas experience a lot of social troubles and have regularly been the place for riots.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The cost of the latest vandalism to occur in the north of Amiens would amount, according to Gilles Demailly, to between four and six million euros.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] These extremely violent riots caused sixteen police officers to be injured.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] An extensive programme of redevelopment of these neighborhoods began recently, with demolition of HLM tower blocks and new infrastructure having been built, especially for schools.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] In 2009, the public transport network of the Amiens agglomeration was significantly modified.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] In 2017, the total number of dwellings in the municipality was 73,541, while it was 63,178 in 1999.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Among this housing, 88.7% were primary residences, 2.1% of secondary residences and 9.2% vacant housing.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] These dwellings were 35.6% of houses and 63.4% of apartments.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The proportion of principal residences, which were the properties of occupants, was 31.9%, down from 2007 (34.4%).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The share of empty rented HLM homes (social housing) was up: 29.8% against 29.4% in 2007, their number increased from 18,268 to 19,431.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] However, this percentage remains much greater than the rate of 20% required by the Law on Solidarity and Urban Renewal (SRU) for cities and agglomerations of more than 50,000 inhabitants.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The identity of the city is strongly marked by the specificity of its housing stock, consisting in a large proportion of detached houses, semi-detached, single or bourgeois: the *amiénoises*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] These traditional houses in the suburbs, in brick, were intrinsically linked to the expansion of the city during and after the Industrial Revolution.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The *amiénoise simple* includes a window on the ground floor and floors for attic and basement.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] It is built on a plot of a few metres wide but is very deep, and includes a garden, forming hearts with green islets and sparse areas.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The *amiénoise double* has two windows at each level.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The *grandes amiénoises* and townhouses rise to at least two floors with large rooms.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] They can have a gate opening onto a paved courtyard.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The official buildings or mansions regularly use brick façades on a sandstone base, decorated by stone window and door frames.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Chanoines neighborhood has stone façades exclusively.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] In historic areas such as the Saint-Leu neighborhood, façades widely use wood, half-timbered or siding, and wattle and daub.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The toponym is derived from the name of the local Gallic people, the Ambiani, which in the 4th century, replaced the old name of the town Samarobriva (the bridge on the Samara – Somme).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Amiens then became the episcopal headquarters.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Amiens municipal council has 55 elected members.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] On 4 April 2014, Brigitte Fouré (IDU (NC)) succeeded Gilles Demailly (PS) as mayor of Amiens.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Her list was elected in the second round on 30 March 2014 with 50.39% of the votes.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Amiens is a city marked by a strong judicial tradition, with the historical presence of its Court of Appeal, the Cour d'appel d'Amiens, as well as all courts of first and second degree of judicial order.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] The Court of Appeal of Amiens has jurisdiction over the three departments of Picardy, with nine high courts.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p01] Amiens also has friendly relations with Mianyang in China and Amiens in Australia.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The inhabitants of Amiens are called the *Amiénois* and their blason populaire is *Chés maqueux d'gueugues* (the eaters of nuts).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The population of Amiens has risen sharply since the mid-19th century: Its population doubled between 1850 and 1960, from 50,000 to 100,000 inhabitants, i.e. a gain of 50,000 people over this period of 110 years, and gaining about 30,000 others since (over 50 years only this time).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Amiens is distinguished by the youthfulness of its population.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Notably the age group 15-24 is much larger (21.2%) than the average of the Somme department (13.2%).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Educational institutions of the city fall under the supervision of the Academy of Amiens which develops curriculum according to the Inspection académique la Somme.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] On 1 September 2010, 10,658 children were enrolled in the Amiens public schools: 4,341 in nursery school and 6,317 in elementary school.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] In 2011, the Amiens agglomeration included 46 nursery schools, six elementary schools and 54 primary schools including eleven private.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] It had nine public colleges and six private colleges.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Amiens metropole welcomes one of the largest student populations in France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] In 2013, the city had 26,000 students (3,300 in short-term) and 800 researchers who are divided into some 40 institutions of higher education, 32 laboratories, and 10 units associated with the National Scientific Research Centre or the French Institute of Health and Medical Research.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Since 2014, the four sites have been gradually gathered on the current site of the South Hospital, with the exception of the long stay units for the elderly remaining in the Saint-Victor Centre.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] This merger will be completed in 2016 and allow the CHU of Amiens to increase its national and inter-regional dimension.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] This group represents the largest hospital construction of France and one of the most important in Europe with more than €630 million for work and equipment.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] At the end of the work, the total space of the CHU of Amiens will be 172,000 square metres (1,850,000 sq ft).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] It will total three blocks of hospitals with 400 beds each.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The CHU of Amiens is the largest employer in the Picardy region.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] At the end of the merger, there will be 6,700 employees, 1,300 students of the health professions, and 1,250 consultants who will go there each day.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] In order to maintain the availability of health units to the north of the city, a health center will open its doors in the first quarter of 2016, at the crossroads of the *Avenue de l'Europe* and the *Rue Maurice-Ravel*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] This health space of 1,200 square metres (13,000 sq ft) will host general practitioners and specialists of the CHU such as: cardiologist, a service of gynaecology-obstetrics, psychologists, dentist, and masseurs-physiotherapists.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] There is a promise of a permanence of care, 7 days a week and 24 hours a day.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Alongside the CHU, there are three private clinics, resulting from the consolidation of old clinics in the city.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] These care and hospitalisation institutions for medical, surgical, and obstetrics came together to create a private hospital center in the Vallée des Vignes neighborhood, south of the city.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The CHU of Amiens figured in 11th place in the *2013 awards of the hospitals and clinics* of the magazine *Le Point*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] In this ranking, the CHU stands out for ankle surgery (3rd), hip prosthesis (5th), foot surgery (7th) and paediatrics (14th).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] In this same classification, the Victor Palmer Health Group, equipped with a solid "mother-to-child hub", gained a 5th place in the table for the gynaecological clinics and an 8th place for breast cancers.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] In 2005, the CHU of Amiens became of international renown thanks to Professor Bernard Devauchelle, a native of the city, where his team performed the first partial face transplant in the world.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Thanks to a large proportion of youth in its population and the dynamism and the success of its sports clubs, Amiens has been awarded the title of "Sportiest city of France" by the *L'Équipe* newspaper in 1999.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The city had already won the title in 1969.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] In 2013, Amiens Métropole had nearly 300 sports associations and Sports Recreation: approximately 150 associations are grouped within the Office of Amiens Metropole Sports and 150 others are referenced without being adherents.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] According to this same Office for Sports, Amiens has 25,000 members of sports clubs, excluding school and university members.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Amiens Spartiates, operating in the top-level Ligue Élite de Football Américain, have been champions of France in 2004, 2010 and 2012.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Created in 1987, the club has more than 400 licensees.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Compagnie d'Arc d'Amiens is an archery club founded on 14 November 1803.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] AUC Athlétisme is a multidisciplinary athletic club which particularly developed Stella Akakpo, specialist of the sprint and the relay.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Bertrand Moulinet specialist of the 20 km and 50 km walk.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The AUC Badminton (Amiens University Badminton Club) was founded in 1986.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Labeled "French school of badminton" by the French Badminton Federation, the club had 205 members in 2014.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The city hosted the French National Badminton Championships in 2011.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Each 15 August at the Parc de la Hotoie, Amiens receives the final stages of Ballon au poing.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Circle of Fencing of Amiens Métropole is one of the oldest French clubs.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] It was succeeded in the Hall of arms of Amiens opened in 1886.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The circle has approximately 150 members and remains a major club of French fencing with many qualifications and results at the French Fencing Championships.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The club held the Elite French Championships in 2001 and 2011.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The team was finalist of the Coupe de France in 2001 and reached semifinals in 1930 and 2008, and played top-division Ligue 1 last time in 2020.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Its associated women's team is CS Amiens Club.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Before the 2012–2013 season, the team was known under the name of CS Amiens Montieres Etouvie.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] AC Amiens is the second biggest club in the city, currently playing in semi-professional Championnat National level.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Golf Club D'amiens was founded in 1924.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The men's team plays in D1, women team in D2.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Amiens Picardie Hand (APH), currently playing in National 2 (D4).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The club, a result of the merger of several Amiens clubs, was created in 1991.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Gothiques d'Amiens, currently playing in Ligue Magnus (D1), were champions of France in 1999 and 2004, and runners-up in France for 1989, 1997, 1998, 2003 and 2006.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The team plays at the Coliséum on the largest area of permanent ice in France (3800 seats).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Amiens hosted Division I of the 2006 Ice Hockey World Championships.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Amiens won the Championship of France in 6/6, 10 times.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Écureuils d'Amiens, Elite League (D1), were the runners-up of France in 2010, finalists of the Coupe de France in 2007 and finalists of the European Cup of clubs in 2008.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Sport Nautique d'Amiens (SNA) was founded in 1866.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Located on the edge of the Parc Saint-Pierre, it is labeled "French rowing school 3 stars" by the French Federation of rowing.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] With 465 members in 2013, the club currently competes in the 2nd division.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Rugby Club Amiénois (RCA) was founded in 1900.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The men's first team plays in Fédérale 3.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Amiens Métropole swim team, is that of Jérémy Stravius, who was a triple world champion of swimming and Olympic champion in the 4 × 100 m relay.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Amiens Sport Table Tennis (ASTT) was founded in 1945.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] It was twice crowned champion of France in 1968 and 1969.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The men's first team also won the Coupe de France in 1966 and 1967.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Amiens Athletic Club (AAC) was founded in 1904.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] It is one of the 10 biggest clubs in France with almost 1,000 members in 2013.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Amiens Longueau Métropole Volley-Ball (ALMVB) including women's first team plays in Women's Elite Division (D2) and the Amiens Métropole Volley-Ball (AMVB).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The men's first team plays in Nationale 1 (D3).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Amiens hosted the finish of Stage 8 of the 2018 Tour de France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] On 29 April 2006, Amiens hosted the French Federation of ice hockey created during the World Cup of Ice Hockey of Group B (antechamber of the world elite) organised in Amiens at the same time.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] It is now installed at Issy-les-Moulineaux.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Each 15 August at the *Parc de la Hotoie*, the city receives the final stages of the Picardy sports and in particular those of the most emblematic, traditional Picard sport: The Ballon au poing.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] This Picard game is played by teams of six.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] To be able to hit the ball, players surround their hand and their wrist with a strip of canvas or leather.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] From August 29 to September 1, 2012, the Compagnie d'Arc d'Amiens organizes the French FITA Archery Championships at the Hippodrome du petit Saint-Jean.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Free newspapers *Metro* and *20 minutes* are distributed in the city, including in Amiens railway station.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Since 7 February 1996, the Communauté d'agglomération Amiens Métropole distributes a free weekly local newspaper: JDA (*Journal des Amiénois*).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] This publication, which appears every Wednesday, is distributed to all homes in the metropolitan area and is made available in public places (taken at about 95,000 copies) as well as on the internet site of the city in its digital version.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Over time, the journal has evolved through various forms.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Carried out by the Directorate of communication of Amiens Métropole, the latest form dates to 16 January 2015.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] In addition to the JDA which is attached to information on the whole of the territory of Amiens Métropole, the city has also had monthly publications specific to the city, which no longer exist today: *Amiensville* then *Amiens Forum* (from April 2009 to June 2014).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The people of Amiens have other sources of information on their territory, such as the monthly publication of the Regional Council of Picardy, *Agir en Picardie*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Departmental Council of the Somme also sees its magazine distributed each month to the samariens homes, *Vivre en Somme*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Since 2006, the regional tourism committee of Picardy publishes *Esprit de Picardie*, a travel magazine on the Picardy region, every six months.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Most of the national radio stations broadcast their programs in the Amiens area and can be added to France Bleu Picardie (100.2 MHz) and local stations Radio Campus Amiens (87.7 MHz) and Radio Galaxie programme Évasion (97.7 MHz).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] As of 1 March 2015, the CSA has not selected Amiens for broadcast or experimentation of this broadcasting standard.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Zen Sōtō Zen centre affiliated with the international Zen Association, on *Rue Vulfran Warmé*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The synagogue in Amiens is located at 12 *Rue du Port d'Amont*, near Pont-Beauville.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has a place of worship on the Doullens road.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The city of Amiens has the largest Muslim community of Picardy and one of the largest in the north of France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Places of worship are evolving, several mosques are in a phase of expansion or relocation.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Several independent prayer rooms are present in the urban community.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] On the other hand, Muslim committees and associations exist in the image of the Islamic Cultural Centre of Amiens in the *Rue de Savoie*, the Muslim Cultural Freedom Association – Institute of Enlightenment and also the Association of residents of the home at 21 *Route d'Allonville*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Protestant Church of Amiens, *Rue Saint-Jacques*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] As both an industrial hub and a services center, Amiens enjoys a large pool of workers with a labor pool of over 350,000 inhabitants and numerous professional training courses.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The magazine *L'Entreprise* elected Amiens "Most attractive city of France" for businesses, in 2009 and 2007, for the category less than 200,000 inhabitants.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The strengths of the city include a developed real estate business and taxation around the average for French cities.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] In addition, its geographical position in the center of the triangle "Paris – London – Brussels", is between three major European cities.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The magazine *Challenges* has also designated Amiens as "Best managed city of France", for the category large cities with more than 100,000 inhabitants, in 2011, 2010 and 2008.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] In 2010, the median taxable household income was €22,539, which placed Amiens at 177th place among the 31,525 communes with more than 39 households in metropolitan France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] In 2017, the proportion of taxable households was 45%.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] In 2017, the population aged 15 to 64 years amounted to 91,555 persons, among which there were 64.5% of assets including 51.4% having a job and 13.1% of unemployed.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] There were 78,284 jobs in the employment area, against 80,908 in 2007.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The number of assets employed and residing in the area of employment being 47,588.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The concentration of jobs indicator is 164.5%, which means that the employment area offers three jobs for every two active inhabitants.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Agriculture has very little representation among Amiens jobs with only 0.2%, just as the construction sector which represents 4.3% of jobs.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Unlike these two sectors whose share is below the national average, the tertiary sector (trade, transport, services) represents a significant part of the Amiens workforce, 42.3%.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Public services (public administration, education, health, social work) accounts for 42.7%.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company announced more than 400 job cuts in May 2008 at the Amiens plant, which has had 1,450 employees; in March 2009, the management announced new collective redundancies of a thousand jobs.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] On 31 December 2015, at Amiens, there were 10,436 businesses: 51 in agriculture, forestry and fisheries, 394 in industry, 685 in construction, 7,110 in trade, transportation and various services and 2,196 were related to the administrative sector.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] In 2018, 1,505 companies had been recorded as being established in Amiens, including 1,206 companies owned by sole proprietors.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Philatelic publishers Yvert et Tellier (catalogues of quotes) and *l'Écho de la timbrologie* (magazine) have their management in Amiens, even if they have more of their services in the Paris region.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Gueudet Group, one of the largest car dealers in France, was established at Amiens in 1918.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The old textile tradition of the city remains with the factory of Lee Cooper France (122 employees).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Since the end of World War II, much of the city's economy was tied to automotive equipment with companies such as Valeo, Goodyear and Sumitomo-Dunlop tires.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] In 2003, the American Goodyear company bought Dunlop.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] These two companies suffered financially through late 2007 and early 2008, and in response, the American Goodyear company headquarters in the United States offered workers a change to their working hours and the number of posts, which a high percentage of staff refused.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Procter & Gamble, settled in Amiens in 1964 to produce soap, and inaugurated its new detergents unit in 1966.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Established on over more than 45 hectares (110 acres), it is one of the largest factories in the world for laundry cleaning products (Ariel, Dash, Bonux, Gama) and for domestic cleaning products (Mr.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] More than 85% of its production is intended for export.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Amiens plant employs approximately 930 people.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Since the mid-1990s, the city has tried to convert the economy towards the internet and telephony industries.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Many call centres (Intracall center, Coriolis France, Médiamétrie) have opened mainly within the city, region or state.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] The Unilog (now Logica) computer service company has installed a service center in Amiens (the CSA).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] Amiens is the seat of the Regional Chamber of commerce and industry of Picardy.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] It is also the seat of the Chamber of commerce and industry of Amiens.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p02] It manages the Amiens - Glisy Aerodrome.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The strategic position of Amiens makes it an attractive destination for a weekend or a few days, from Paris, Lille or Brussels.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Amiens also benefits from the proximity of the Baie de Somme, a tourist hotspot registered at the Club des plus belles baies du monde and labelled Great Site of France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Amiens has the label of Towns and Lands of Art and History since 1992.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Within this framework, the host of the heritage organises guided tours on themes intended for an audience of adults and children, with educational workshops.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] A signposted circuit allows an independent tour of the town, with information panels offering comment on places and notable buildings.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Amiens has an important historical and cultural heritage, and an accessible and varied natural heritage, on which tourism is based.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The main attractions are the cathedral, which is included in the world heritage of UNESCO, the *hortillonnages*, Jules Verne House, the Tour Perret, the Musée de Picardie, the zoo, and the Saint-Leu and Saint-Maurice neighborhoods.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The information given below is relative only to a brief selection.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The city is famous for its Notre-Dame Cathedral, masterpiece of Gothic art and one of the largest cathedrals in the world by its interior volume (200,000 m3 (7,100,000 cu ft)).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The largest religious and medieval building of France, its interior could twice hold Notre-Dame de Paris.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The cathedral measures 145 metres (476 ft) long and its spire rises 112 metres (367 ft) high.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The vaults of the central nave, finished in 1247, are 42.3 metres (139 ft), close to the maximum limit for this architecture.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Dating back to the 13th century, its construction is due to the wealth of the city in the Middle Ages and to the fire of the Romanesque cathedral which stood previously.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Three architects, including Robert of Luzarches succeeded to complete the construction.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Amiens Cathedral is notable for the coherence of its plan, the beauty of its three-tier interior elevation, the particularly fine display of sculptures on the principal façade and in the south transept, and inlays of its floor.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Regarded as the archetype of the classic Gothic style, the cathedral also presents some elements of the radiant Gothic style and flamboyant Gothic.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The speed of construction, barely 70 years for the shell (1220 to 1269), explains this remarkable homogeneity of style.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Its façade is decorated with more than 3,000 statues, gargoyles and chimeras.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Registered since 1981 as a World Heritage Site of UNESCO, it is a "masterpiece of world heritage".
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] For a second time in 1998, it is a monumental step on the Camino de Santiago.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Despite the two World Wars of the 20th century, which severely affected the city, it managed to stay intact.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] A show of the reproduction of the original polychromy of façades, discovered as a result of recent laser cleaning, is given annually for free in December and during the summer period.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The show is a projection on the façade of slides in color.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The zodiac is a set of reliefs on the foundations of the western façade formed series of quatrefoil medallions, carved in a representative agrarian calendar and the signs of the zodiac.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The statue of the weeping Angel that is on a tomb carved by Nicolas Blasset, and the reliefs evoking Saint-Firmin and St.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] John the Baptist, are some of the well-known works of the cathedral.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] At ground level lies the intact labyrinth of 234 metres (768 ft) long.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] On the north side of the cathedral is the former Palace of the Bishop of Amiens, occupied by the École supérieure de commerce in Amiens.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The origin of the Belfry of Amiens dates back to the establishment of the commune of Amiens by Louis VI.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] It is mentioned for the first time in an arbitral award issued by the chapter of Amiens in 1244.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Symbolizing the independence of the commune, it was formerly used for meetings of the notables of the city and then as archive rooms, weapons store and prison.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] A spotter nearby monitored arrivals and warned the population of the external dangers.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] During the Middle Ages, the building was repeatedly engulfed by fire.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The belfry is composed of a base in white cut stone, built in the 15th century between 1406 and 1410, a stone superstructure bell tower built from 1749 with Baroque volutes at its base, and a dome covered with slate and then the renowned arrow weather vane.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] At the time, a huge 11-ton bell was installed inside, it was later destroyed along with the dome, whose copper component melted, in the bombardment and fire of the city on 19 May 1940.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Abandoned and devoid of a roof since World War II, the monument was fully restored between February 1989 and July 1990.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Located on the *Place au Fil*, the old central square of the city before the arrival of the railway and the rise of the *Rue des Trois Calloux*, the belfry is adjacent to *Les Halles* and the back of the *Hôtel de Ville* (city hall).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] At a height of 52 metres (171 ft), it rings every hour of the day.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Since July 2005, the belfry of Amiens is a UNESCO World Heritage Site, as part of a set of 56 Belfries of Belgium and France which were inscribed because of their architecture and their importance in the rise of municipal power in Northern France and Belgium.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The belfry is also recorded in the inventory of Historic Monuments.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] In 1845, the traditional fair of Saint-Jean, formerly held at *Place René Goblet*, was transferred to *Place Longueville*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] It is a wide esplanade that took the place of the Longueville bastion, after the demolition of the city walls in the early 19th century.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Each year, a temporary circus is established for this occasion.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] In 1865, a circus company emerged to claim a permanent circus, which would be built in wood by the Schytte contractor in 1874.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] However, expensive maintenance prompted the municipality to consider the construction of a new building.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The decision was made in 1886 under the leadership of Mayor Frédéric Petit and the work began.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The Chief Architect of the Somme, Émile Ricquier, a disciple of Gustave Eiffel, was responsible for its construction.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] It was inspired by the Cirque d'hiver of Paris but with a cast metal frame, supplemented by brick from the local countryside.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The architect of civil buildings, Charles Garnier, claimed that the frames should be hidden with a plaster imitating stone.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The "moderninst" design of Ricquier, who chose to display the structure, and to favor local material such as brick, is visible at the rear of the monument.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] With its 16-sided polygonal shape and a diameter of 44 metres (144 ft), it includes lodges and stalls in its enclosure.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] As a completely modern project, it hosted two steam engines, dedicated to fully electric lights and central heating.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Since its construction, it was also the first circus which included a buffet and a refreshment bar.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The cost of the construction of the building finally reached double the forecast.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The roof was damaged by a shell in 1916.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The circus was the setting for Federico Fellini's *The Clowns* (1971), and the film by Jean-Jacques Beineix, *Roselyne and the Lions* (1989), with Isabelle Pasco as lead actress.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The largest of the circuses of the province with its 3,000-seats, the building has acquired a multidisciplinary use for decades of performances of theatre, dance, concerts, galas, sports and public meetings.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Renovated in 2003, it now bears the name of Cirque Jules-Verne.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] After hosting the performances of Cirque Rancy, it hosts resident Cirque Arlette Gruss.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Since 1 January 2011, the circus has been labelled "national hub circus and street arts", managed by an EPCC.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] It is one of seven in France and is still in use today.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] In 1882, Jules Verne and his wife, Honorine, rented the house at the corner of *Rue Charles-Dubois* and *Boulevard Longueville* until 1900.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Acquired in 1980 by the city, the house is labeled Maisons des Illustres by the Ministry of Culture.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Restored in 2006, thanks to the work of the Centre international Jules-Verne, this 19th-century mansion, registered as a national heritage site, traces through the exhibition of more than 700 objects, the personality, the sources of inspiration and memories of Jules Verne.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Opposite the Gare d'Amiens, is located the Tour Perret (from the name of its architect Auguste Perret).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Over 100 metres (330 ft) high, it was one of the first skyscrapers built in Europe, and the highest for a long time.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The Église Saint-Leu d'Amiens was built at the end of the 15th century, on the model of the hall-churches.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] It is dedicated, as its district, to Saint Leu, referring to the 7th century bishop who was exiled to the Vimeu.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] A flamboyant portal adorns the base of the steeple.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The latter, struck by lightning, had to be rebuilt at the beginning of the 16th century.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Stone and wood statues date from the 17th century.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The choir houses the glory of the Duthoit brothers.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Amiens has 270 hectares (670 acres) of green space (excluding communal woodland) 118,300 hectares (292,000 acres) of *hortillonnages*, 300 hectares (740 acres) of forests, 30 hectares (74 acres) of marshland, in addition to its river and its streams.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Floral City awarded the maximum score of 4 flowers in the floral contest of cities and villages of France to Amiens, and it offers a particularly rich wooded heritage.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] With 38,650 trees (excluding woodland), of which 17,000 are situated on highways, Amiens to win the national tree award.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] In 2014, the city ranked in the top 10 greenest cities of France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Presenting itself as a city concerned with the environment, Amiens has made the link between the city and nature a central axis of its metropolitan development project called *Amiens 2030*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Amiens is also known for the hortillonnages, gardens on small islands in over 300 hectares (740 acres) of marshland between the River Somme and River Avre, surrounded by a grid network of human-made canals (locally known as "rieux").
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] They are also known as the "floating gardens of Amiens".
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The *hortillonnages* are sometimes called "Little Venice of the North", because of the canals.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Prior to its opening in May 1952, the Amiens Zoo is a green space bordering the basin of the Park of the Hotoie.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] It was the mayor of the time, Maurice Vast, who decided to develop the site in 1949.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Originally intended as an entertainment venue, the zoo began its mission of conservation, education and research between 1970 and 1980.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Between 1990 and 2000, the zoo was completely renovated and became a permanent member of the European Association of Zoos and Aquaria (EAZA) in 2001 and the National Association of Zoological Parks (ANPZ) in 2002.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Today, there are 300 animals, representing approximately 75 species from all continents, cohabiting on 6.5 hectares (16 acres).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] They live in environments, which are close to their natural environment, favouring their well-being.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Traditionally, entry is free on 14 July, Bastille Day.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Parc du Grand Marais, along the Somme Canal, to the west of the city.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Covering over 25 hectares (62 acres), this park has many sports facilities: American football stadium, skate bowl, football field, play structures.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Jardin des plantes originally called the *Jardin du Roy*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] Created in 1751, it is the oldest garden of Amiens on the *Boulevard du jardin des plantes*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] As a floral city, 4 flowers were awarded in 2013 by the National Council of Cities and Villages of France for the competition of floral cities and villages.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p03] The national Council of Cities and Villages awarded the 2012 National Tree Prize to the city for "its exceptional and innovative management of its wooded heritage" with its 37,000 trees, some more than a century old.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Amiens was strongly tipped to host the Louvre II.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] The city has a number of concert spaces, mostly small venues, and pubs also host numerous concerts throughout the year.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Amiens Métropole has nine cultural centers which cover much of the metropolitan area: six in various districts of Amiens, and three in the neighbouring communes of Longueau, Camon and Glisy.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] These outreach facilities working in the field of art and creation are openly oriented "venues".
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Open to all, they offer an eclectic programme; theatre and concerts, shows for young people and dance, projections of films, exhibitions, meetings and debates.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] The Bibliothèques d'Amiens Métropole is a network of 28 facilities spread over the whole territory of the metropolis.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] The heart of this network is the Louis Aragon library, located on *Rue de la République*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Built between 1823 and 1826, it is one of the oldest municipal libraries in France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] It experienced several improvements, including campaigns of work between 1982 and 1993, which have endowed it with new spaces: Two auditoriums, a youth space, a library and an art library.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Registration and borrowing is free for all of the people of Amiens in all libraries.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Two libraries also provide service to neighborhoods and the communes of the agglomeration, and there is home delivery of documents for people with reduced mobility.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Throughout the year, Amiens is the seat of many cultural, traditional or economic events.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Even if it rarely achieves national notoriety (with the notable exceptions of Les Fatals Picards, The Rabeats, Olympe, Albin de la Simone, Disiz and Rokia Traoré), the Amiens music scene is active and developed.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] In this dynamic, the New French Rock scene holds a central place and is organised around a collective, *Amiens Burning*, which is responsible for networking the breeding ground for the local rock scene, to accompany its projects, and organize concerts.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Since their creation, La Lune des Pirates and Cité Carter also provide support to the local scene.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] For example, the Cité Carter produces a compilation each year, with local groups.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Classical music is represented by the Orchestre de Picardie and the University Orchestra of Picardy.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Vocal practice is represented by the Regional Choir of Picardy, the University Choir of Picardie, and the Choir of France Picardy.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] One can also include the Harmony Saint-Pierre, a fanfare of 70 musicians, which has become a local institution since its inception in 1894.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] The city has the Conservatoire à rayonnement régional d'Amiens, seat of strong musical activity (framed by 70 teachers, an administrative and technical team with an additional 20 people).
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Amiens saw rise, over the centuries, to major writers.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] In the first half of the 17th century, Vincent Voiture, poet and letter writer, was the darling of the Précieuses for the fluidity of his style.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] In 1634, he was member of the 1st Académie française.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] In 1678, Charles du Fresne, sieur du Cange, nicknamed "the French Varro", published his *Glossarium* in 3 volumes.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] This glossary of medieval Latin is still authoritative today.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] In 1750, Jean Baptiste Gresset, a playwright and poet who was celebrated in his time and was a member of the Académie française, founded the Academy of Amiens which is still active today.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] In 1782, the Amiens native Choderlos de Laclos published *Les Liaisons dangereuses* where he staged a depraved nobility.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Considered one of the masterpieces of 18th-century literature, the book has toured the world and is known as an Oscar-winning film adaptation.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] In the 19th century, there was a brilliant literary life around the Académie des sciences, des lettres et des arts d'Amiens with historian Albéric de Calonne and the Yvert family.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] However, the great name of Amiens literary life is Jules Verne.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] He animated all intellectual activity, giving balls and parties, while his wife held a famous salon.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] He often attended the library of the industrial society, which subscribed to numerous scientific journals.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Engaged in local life, he was Councillor of Amiens from 1888 to 1904.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] He was closely interested in the affairs of the city, wrote many reports on the theatre and brought its support to the construction of the municipal circus.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Amiens does appear explicitly in his novels but there are however characteristic elements of the city such as the cathedral and the river.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] This is the case, for example, for the imaginary city of Ragz in *Le secret de Wilhem Storitz*.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] In the novel *Une fantaisie du docteur Ox*, the inhabitants of the fictional town of Virgamen, the Virgamenois, refer directly to the Amiénois and their prudent nature.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] In 1875, he delivered before the Academy of Sciences, Letters and Arts of Amiens a speech entitled "An ideal city: Amiens in the year 2000" where he portrays himself wandering in a forward-thinking city of Amiens.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p04] Since then, the city has built a tourist route from this text.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] He died in Amiens in 1905, and he deeply marked the town's footprint, so that today many places, monuments and events bear his name.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] He rests at La Madeleine cemetery where one can read on his tomb: *Vers l'immortalité et l'éternelle jeunesse.* [Towards immortality and eternal youth].
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] In 1885, Englishman John Ruskin published the Bible of Amiens, which was translated into French, extensively annotated and prefaced, in 1904, by Marcel Proust.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] This book dedicated to Notre-Dame d'Amiens was the opportunity for Proust to recall his admiration for the English author and the Cathedral of Amiens.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] In the second half of the 19th century, Jules Barni, Member of Parliament for the Somme, Associate Professor of philosophy and brilliant scholar translated Kant's work in French and thus enabled its dissemination in France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] A native of Amiens, Paul Bourget published *Le Disciple* in 1889, a novel today considered his major work.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] He was elected, 5 years later, to the Académie française.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] Born in Sainte-Anne district in 1885, Roland Dorgelès published *Les Croix de bois* in 1919.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] A masterpiece written from his notes taken at the Front, the novel won the Prix Femina the same year.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] Though capable of obtaining the Prix Goncourt, it was beaten by À l'ombre des jeunes filles en fleurs by Marcel Proust, 6 votes against 4.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] A member of the Académie Goncourt in 1929, he was elected president in 1954 until his death in 1973.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] In 1926, the Amiens native Henri Deberly, won the Prix Goncourt with Le Supplice de Phèdre, a novel inspired by his home city.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] Many films or scenes from films were shot in Amiens and its surroundings.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] Amiens is a stronghold of comics in France.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] A whole generation of designers and Amiens writers make the city an important creative center of the 9th art.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] The main actors in this generation, include Régis Hautière, Norédine Allam who notably led the recolouring of the 33 Asterix albums in the framework of the project "The great collection" and also Antoine Dodé, David François, Fraco, Hardoc, Greg Blondin, and Nicolas Hitori De.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] The city was also the birthplace or home of big names in the comic strip universe, such as the Amiens native Joseph Pinchon, creator of the character of *Bécassine*; Paul Gillon, winner of the Grand Prix de la ville d'Angoulême and also Philippe Thirault.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] Actor of this dynamic around the BD, the association *On a marché sur la bulle* [Explorers on the bubble] organises the Rendez-vous de la bande dessinée d'Amiens, one of the greatest French comic book festivals.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] Active throughout the territory, the structure also manages a resource center and has an editorial department with the Éditions de la Gouttière.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] Amiens, in the image of the Picardy region, has a rich gastronomic heritage.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] The region is also known for "flamiche aux poireaux", a puff pastry tart made with leeks and cream.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] The Summer Rambo apple cultivar originated near Amiens in the 16th century.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] Marie Denizard (1872-1959), in January 1913, the first woman to stand as a candidate in a French presidential election.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/amiens-p05] In 1991, the municipality formed around Gilles de Robien designed a new logo, incorporating the Fleur-de-lis and the Ivy leaf present on the coat of arms, placed side by side in red with a background of grey or white, depending on usage.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/andré-de-brancas] He fought for the Catholic League and the Spanish, wishing to make Normandy an independent lordship.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/andré-de-brancas] He remained in Rouen even after the abjuration of Henry IV of France, and did not submit until 1594.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/andré-de-brancas] He was made an Admiral of France on 23 August 1594.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/andré-de-brancas] In 1595 he was captured and killed by the Spanish at the Siege of Doullens.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] Born in Parma, Antonio was the third son of Ranuccio II Farnese, Duke of Parma, and his wife Maria d'Este of the Modena.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] At the age of 18, Prince Antonio embarked on a Grand Tour of Europe with the intention of establishing contacts in courts across the continent; however, he simply dissipated 1,580,000 lire on galas.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] As a prince he spent most of his time at the court of his cousin the Hereditary Prince of Modena, because his sister-in-law, Duchess Dorothea Sophia, banned masques and other merriments, distractions which Antonio revelled in.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] The castle of Sala, which he zealously enlarged and renovated, served as his Parmese residence.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] Here, Antonio threw lavish parties frequented by his favourite and mistress, the "domineering" Countess Margherita Bori Giusti.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] By the time of his accession in February 1727, the morbidly obese Antonio had scant desire to rule.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] His life of hedonism continued unperturbed: he stayed up all night, sat for dinner one hour before dawn, played faro and basset and attended Countess Bori's salons on a daily basis.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] As there was no heir to the duchy, the secretary of state, Count Anvidi, and Bori coerced an unwilling Antonio to marry Enrichetta d'Este, the sister of his friend the Hereditary Prince of Modena.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] On 21 July 1727 the marriage contract was signed.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] His bride was adored by the people of Parma, and Antonio treated her kindly.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] The marriage, despite all Antonio's attempts at conception, was childless.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] Believing the treaty would not remain in force, Elizabeth obtained in 1729 France's permission to install 6,000 Spanish troops in Parma.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] France further agreed to repudiate the Holy Roman Emperor Charles VI's claim of suzerainty over the duchy.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] An incensed Charles VI responded by stationing 40,000 soldiers in his Duchy of Milan, north of Parma.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] In the midst of the diplomatic fray Antonio died, ostensibly from a boil, caused, according to a contemporary, by often sporting "a wig that was too hot for him".
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] Thus ended the House of Farnese, who for 184 years had served as sovereigns to Parma and Piacenza.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] Six days after his death on 20 January 1731, Austrian troops marched into the Duchy of Parma and Piacenza, intent on staying there until Spain re-subscribed to the terms of the Treaty of London.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] However, it was soon discovered that Antonio's will left the country to "the pregnant stomach of my wife".
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] Pope Clement XII, the King of France, and Elisabeth Farnese doubted Enrichetta's pregnancy.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] They were correct: Austria convinced Enrichetta that she was pregnant to keep the Bourbons out of Italy long enough for it to occupy Parma.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] Upon discovering she was in fact not pregnant, Spain and Austria put aside their differences so as not to worsen the "precarious state of European affairs".
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] The ensuing *rapprochement* saw Charles of Spain mount the ducal throne as a vassal of the Emperor.
[src:alexander-farnese-duke-of-parma/antonio-farnese] Charles, after resigning the throne of Parma in 1735, took all the Farnese treasures, including several pieces by Correggio, the Farnese Collection of Ancient sculpture, the Ducal library and archives and the Ducal Palace's marble staircase, with him to Naples, the seat of his new kingdom.
